text: Saw the Kyoto show at the met museum of art again I highly recommend it Felt a profound sense of kinship with the work some of it is just instinctual as if I ve held the paintings from the past edo period and more in my heart in my senses the diaphanous worlds unfolding the ground and sky as one the vessels and bodies of water and wind ornamental and simple wonderful to feel my new work of innerscape paintings having connective tissue with the th century works and still being wholly contemporary engagements

text: Please vote for me I entered a contest at the Metropolitan Museum of Art The contest is almost over it will be closed for voting on August th The way the contest works is that the artwork with the most votes goes to a jury If the jury selections your artwork it will be made into a piece of artwork to be sold in the metropolitan museums store I really hope that I get a chance to be judged So please vote for me the link is in my bio You will get a confirmation from the Metropolitan Museum of art once you get the confirmation you have to answer it or the vote won t count So please vote for me the link is in my bio art artistoninstagram artist themet metropolitanmuseumofart metropolitanmuseumofart metmuseum nyc nycskyline nycskyscrapers hudson hudsonriver womenartists womanart womanartist fauvist colorful landscape artcontest metstore femaleartist femaleartists artforeveryone

text: Insomniac III by JacobKainen American Monotype in color Signed and dated by the artist Jacob Kainen was a painter printmaker journalist scholar collector and curator Kainen was born in Waterbury Connecticut in He studied at the Art Students League and Pratt Institute Shortly after the artist joined the John Reed Club and met Diego Rivera Henry Glintenkamp George Ault and Stuart Davis In Kainen had his first solo exhibition mounted at the A C A Gallery In he was appointed curator of the Division of Graphic Arts at the National Museum of American History in Washington D C Kainen also worked as a curator of prints and drawings for years at the National Collection or Fine Arts now the Smithsonian American Art Museum He retired from that position in In a retrospective of Kainen s work was mounted at the National Collection of Fine Arts Jacob Kainen died March in Chevy Chase Maryland at the age of His work can be found in numerous collections and major museums worldwide

text: Mourning Victory by Daniel Chester French Commission for the Melvin Memorial The piece was commission by James C Melvin to honor his three brothers who died fighting for the Union in the Civil War The sculpture depicts an angel coming out from under the ravages of war She is shrouded with an American flag and if you look close you can see the stars of the flag above her head In the second photo you can see the feathers of the angel s wing revealed on the side Such a beautiful and powerful image to honor those who fought for the freedom of ALL men and women and defeated the evil institution of legalized slavery met metropolitanmuseumofart sculpture marble civilwar union jamescmelvin danielchesterfrench carving angel flag star memorial mourningvictory history museum victorian nouveau wing peace

text: Coney Island yesterday was an incredible time Building community and inspiring curiosity Nothing feels better than coming together for something greater than yourself Great work to post soon Hope to see you at the Met If you are at the Met today you will find power and purpose If you are elsewhere we send power your way We seek we gain Today is a marvelous day Today is another day with infinite possibilities That alone is inspiring Every day is unpredictable It can be unpredictable for the greatest of reasons Today we can become millionaires Today we can change the world Today we can revolutionize art Today we can make someone feel significant All of these outcomes are unpredictable and infinite Let possiblity guide you through this day We hope to see you and where ever you find yourself all power is with you AOTM aotmatconey artistsofthemet artcollective coneyisland boardwalksketch metmuseum met metropolitanmuseumofart collectivepower unify forart nycollective

text: You may notice that many of Lorica s designs are based on later armors from the th and th century The reason I m drawn to these pieces is for details like these from a Dutch cuirassier armor at metarmsandarmor By this time armor was at its height as an art form and fashion even as it waned on the battlefield When I m choosing pieces to adapt I try to look for designs that are recognizably distinct from one another No offense to my th and th century afficionados out there but once you ve seen one white armor or German Gothic harness you ve sort of seen them all I love those periods and styles to death but the individuality and variety in later pieces is just exquisite armsandarmor armor armour metropolitanmuseumofart metmuseum metarmsandarmor thcentury thcentury historicalfashion historynerd historygeek historyjunkie historymuseum knight armorer medievalhistory renaissancestyle medievalfashion renaissancefashion

text: There s definitely no shortage of great museums in newyork The metropolitanmuseumofart often shortened to just the Met is another example of this It currently hosts an exhibition featuring the instruments of many famous rocknroll musicians such as Chuck Berry Jerry Lee Lewis Prince Eric Clapton and Jimmy Page but its permanent collection is nothing to scoff at either Another exhibition is dedicated to the concept of campy culture and its influence on modern fashion In fact there s so much to see at the Met we only managed to scratch the surface of everything it has to offer Luckily our entry tickets are valid for several days so we plan to go back tomorrow manhattan unitedstates nofilter

text: Finally I got to see Leonardo da Vinci s Saint Jerome in the wilderness at metropolitanmuseumofart today The moment that I set my eyes on it the agonizing figure immediately influenced me The muscles in the face and neck are almost anatomical and it conveys strong emotions Second is by Rembrandt rembrandt a Dutch school master dutchschool It shows Rembrandt s meditation on the meaning of fame by depicting a scene that Aristotle put his hand on a bust sculpture of Alexander the Great Who is immortal Third another Rembrandt with his signature dark palette portrait painting artlover artysciencee artcollection artcollector saintjerome leonardodavinci awesomeart oilpainting artist artistsoninstagram artistsoninstagram artappreciation arthistory

text: The Winged Bull and Lion are but two of the sculptures showcased from the Assyrian capital city of Nimrud ancient Kalhu in a space designed to evoke their original palace setting The ancient state of Assyria lay in what is now northern Iraq The sculptures in the gallery all date to the reign of Ashurnasirpal II r B C a king whose military expeditions to the west reached the shores of the Mediterranean Sea and helped lay the foundations for an empire that would eventually encompass the entire Near East These colossal winged bull and lions were two of many that stood as guardians in the ancient Near Eastern palace They confronted visitors and helped to ward off evil spirits and demons The Metropolitan Museum s bull and lion originally formed part of two gateways in a courtyard In antiquity each gateway was guarded by a matching pair either two bulls or two lions excerpts from the MET Winged Bull and Lion B C in the Assyrian Sculpture Court Department of Ancient Near Eastern Art metmuseum wingedbullandlion artoftheday artoflooking assyriansculpture assyriansculpturecourt metropolitanmuseumofart myphotography myphoto antiquity

text: I M A NEW YORKER Ich bin ein Berliner I am Berliner is a famous phrase pronounced by the president of the United States John F Kennedy on June in West Berlin on the balcony of the building of the Rathaus Sch neberg then the town hall from West Berlin when Willy Brandt was their mayor Yesterday Saturday August I repeated I m a New Yorker The previous Thursday I had received the New York City Identification Card in the mail This card is a valid identification document for the New York police It also allows you to enter the best museums in the city for free get discounts on medications and many more advantages I spent the day at the Metropolitan Museum which is open from in the morning until at night Before as an active New Yorker among trees and meadows I traveled from north to south in Central Park about miles greeting the morning sun I will not talk about the Metropolitan Museum MET I will only mention Luisa Ignacia Rold n Villavicencio Seville September baptism date Madrid January La Roldana She is a great figure of baroque sculpture Of her three terracotta of small dimensions are exhibited Three exceptional jewels I illustrate them with mobile photos of the pile which give what they can of it This morning the blackbird s trill woke me up which has landed on the window sill La vita bella Life is Beautiful newyork newyorkcity newyork world newyorkgram newyorklovers newyorklike newyorker newyorkers newyorkerstyle met metropolitan metropolitanmuseum metropolitanmuseumsculpture centralpark centralpark baroc barocco barocostyle sculpture sculptures themet museum museo metropolitanmuseumofart newyorkcity manhattan paintings painting instagood themetropolitanmuseumofart

text: th century Persian rug Metropolitan Museum of Art New YorkThis prayer rug or sajjadah identified by its central niche design the Qur anic inscriptions in its border and the names of God in its spandrels is consistent with a group of carpets thought to have been a diplomatic gift from the Safavid Shah Abbas I to the Ottoman sultan Murad III r Because some of the verses promote a Shiite perspective by referring to the intercession of Shiite imams with God the group was apparently never used by the Sunni Ottomans This carpet feature warps in two colors one of a natural undyed fiber and the other of a rarely seen intense red that are arranged in an irregular pattern Microscopic investigation has revealed remnants of the original selvage or the woven edge which is similar to some of those found on the masterpiece Safavid Carpets from the early sixteenth century Silk warp and weft wool pile metal wrapped thread asymmetricaly knotted thread brocaded Dimensions Rug L in cm W in cm

text: Qu es Camp Camp es verbo sustantivo y adjetivo Camp lo defini Susan Sontag con su poema del mismo nombre en y fue la base del tema de la exhibici n de este a o en el Museum of Art s Costume Institute del Museo Metropolitano de la ciudad de Nueva York La exhibici n tiene como centro el poema de Sontag y piezas de dise adores y casas de alta costura como Moschino off white ysl y dem s Realmente un espect culo visitar y ver como el concepto de Camp da riendas libres con sus frases expuestas en cada recuadro con piezas que lo complementan como Gender without Genitals A second Childhood Cultural Slumming Camp sees everything in quotations Camp is Failed Seriousness The hallmark of Camp is the spirit of extravagance Camp is a woman walking around in a dress made of three million feathers Camp is productively anachronistic and critically renders specific historical norms obsolete Les dejo en mis stories m s fotos del libro y de la misma exhibici n para que conozcan las dualidades que Camp nos muestra las extravagancias las cosas del pueblo y de las masas los lujos y la elusiva realeza del mundo de la moda que seg n Sontag solo ellos entender n qu realmente es Camp

text: A circa jade onyx diamond enamel and platinum dress ornament by Georges Fouquet French The piece measures a mammoth x x inches In Georges Fouquet took over the the Paris jewelry firm that was established by his father in He moved the firm s styles towards something more modern continuing to supply his fashionable clientele with exquisite jewels in the latest styles through the s Fouquet like many artists during the French Art Deco era was influenced by the exoticism of the Far East This particular dress ornament typifies the theatrical nature of the style The large scale and weight of the ornament suggests that it was probably intended to be an exhibition piece rather than one to be worn regularly georgefouquet artdeco artdecojewelry french france diamond diamondjewelry chinese jade theatrical jewelryhistory jewelrydesigner jewelryart jewelryartist couturejewelry museum met metropolitanmuseumofart NewYork gemstone gemstonejewelry fashion luxury luxuryjewelry jewelry jewelrygram instajewelry vintage jewelryaddict ilovejewelry

text: A vase of flowersMargareta Haverman Dutch Breda A vase of flowers stands on a stone it s contents spilling forth from the surrounding alcove Visible on the heavily shadowed vase perhaps made of terracotta or gilt bronze are vegetable ornamentation and a grotesque face The bouquet belonging to no particular season ranges from roses and hydrangeas to lilies and an opium poppy A white and maroon variegated tulip crowns the arrangement its surface dotted with dewdrops Special details a butterfly perches on one petal and a housefly on another Flies a snail and swarming ants animate the still life Cluster of green and red grapes along with a peach rest against the vase obscuring its foot Hints of decay in form of discoloration mark the leaves haverman vaseofflowers roses lilies tulip butterfly snail womanpainter dutchpainter metropolitanmuseumofart

text: Fra Carnevale The Birth of the Virgin detail tempera and oil on wood Metropolitan Museum of Art New York Breaking with convention the artist shows the Madonna s birth in contemporary terms In the background the newborn baby is bathed by midwives while in the foreground women greet each other The imposing palace patterned on the Ducal Palace of Urbino is decorated with reliefs derived from Roman sculpture The picture is from an altarpiece commissioned in for Santa Maria della Bella in Urbino a companion panel is in the Museum of Fine Arts Boston In Florence Fra Carnevale worked with Filippo Lippi he also knew the paintings of Piero della Francesca and probably met the architect theorist Leon Battista Alberti FraCarnevale BartolomeodiGiovanni TheBirthoftheVirgin MetropolitanMuseumofArt RenaissanceArt ItalianPaintings palazzoducaleurbino Urbino Painting Arthistory Art Arte pittura historicalcostume

text: My first opportunity to see Emanuel Leutze s painting of Washington Crossing the Delaware was back in Staff at my school site had been sent to Brooklyn for a conference on school improvement but I spent a chunk of my time escaping from sessions and going on walkabout over to Manhattan despite it being January with temperatures near freezing One of my first stops was the Metropolitan Museum of Art where I stumbled upon the American Wing of the Museum Still teaching fifth grade at the time I was immediately convinced that the wing was what History Teacher Heaven had to look like Paul Revere John Adams Alexander Hamilton among others and then this painting covering one wall Wow Just wow The sheer size of it The next time I returned to New York City two years later the American Wing was closed for refurbishment so when the chance arose to go back to New York City this summer I made damn sure I had a chance to see it again Partly it was because I wanted to see where the Met had moved the piece and partly because my original photograph which I often shared with my students in class elicited giggles simply because in my quest to show the painting s size there was a nude statue randomly placed fairly close to the painting Measuring feet x feet the size of the painting still astonishes me years after seeing it the first time But what s even more amazing to me now is that in my desire to take yet another better photo to show my students the painting s relative size there s that blasted nude statue hehheh AmericanWing EmanuelLeutze WashingtonCrossingtheDelaware washingtononyourside AmericanHistory HistoryTeacher metropolitanmuseumofart TheMet themetfifthavenue CentralPark Manhattan MidtownManhattan etsicvadit

text: This sculpture is the marble version of Perseus with the Head of Medusa that Canova carved for Countess Valeria Tarnowska He wrote that he was also shipping a plaster of the Medusa head lest the marble one add too much weight to the statue s outstretched arm The countess could attach the lighter plaster to the arm instead and placing a lit candle inside the marble one which is hollow she could watch the eerie light effects Like many other Neoclassical Medusa heads Canova s is based on the ancient marble mask the Rondanini Medusa at the Glyptothek of Munich The motif of the severed head of Medusa teeming with snakes became one of the most characteristic subjects for cameos The image of the head perfectly suits the round field of a tondo Artists were challenged to capture in the motif a perfect stasis between the macabre and the sublime Generations versed in the classics knew that Perseus presented the head to the goddess Minerva and that it thenceforth embellished her breastplate By implication it served the wearer as a protective talisman tacitly announcing the triumph of good over evil metmuseum Head of Medusa Studio of Antonio Canova Plaster cast with modern metal rod Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum T te de M duse Atelier d Antonino Canova Fonte de pl tre avec tige en m tal moderne Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum th post of DailyMuseum This week Sculpture of Medusa

name: 2019-08-14 09.05.11 2109911829295007417_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: This is one of multiple works we have in our home by Leonard Lehrer As an RN my wife used to help care for a young girl Anna Katrina Lehrer when we first met in Arizona Anna was born with cerebral palsy and Jamie helped Anna s parents Marilyn and Leonard with her care I had just started painting in college and Jamie said I should meet Mr Lehrer At the time Leonard was the Chair of ASU s art department and the Founding Director of the School of Art I recall the first visit to their house original art by known artists from around the world filled every inch of every wall As blown away as I was with this I was equally impressed with their kindness and guidance that followed Shortly after the initial meetings Leonard took a position as Chair of the Department of Art Art Professions at NYU It was there I had the pleasure of staying with Leonard and his family in their downtown residence He was my personal tour guide through NYC the Met MoMA Whitney and other art museums He took me to visit numerous galleries treated me to amazing restaurants took me grocery shopping for what would become one of Marilyn s gourmet meals and most importantly shared his views and understanding of art with me As temporary as it was I was under his wing Years have passed since our last communication they were in Texas It was based on art and ended with one of these days we d love to see you guys again Today while searching for his contact information I found out he had passed over a year ago To say I m saddened is an understatement but I m grateful of my time with him and the advice experience and guidance he provided I ve seen a part of him everyday for years but tonight his work will be even more special and my brushstrokes will be for him Do yourself a favor and go visit leonardlehrer com leonardlehrer lithograph lithography printmaking metropolitanmuseumofart

text: This morning in the Drawings and Prints study room we had the pleasure of focusing on the botanical studies and book cover designs of American artist Margaret Neilson Armstrong Alongside Sarah Whyman Whitman and Alice C Morse she was one of the trailblazing female book artists of her day After a career of over years she turned from designing book covers to the careful study of all the wild flowers native to the United States resulting in her publication Western Wild Flowers of The Met is fortunate to have two albums filled with her preparatory studies as well as many of her beautiful bindings and publications bookart artofthebook bookcoverdesign judgeabookbyitscover california margaretarmstrong femaleartist americanartists botanicalstudies westernwildflowers pocketbook watercolors flowers trailblazer studyroom printsanddrawings metonpaper metdrawingsandprints metcollection metcurator metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart

text: Edward Hopper American From Williamsburg Bridge Oil on canvas In From Williamsburg Bridge Hopper depicts the austere facades of four apartment buildings and reduces the steel suspension bridge that gives the painting its name to the margins Completed in and connecting Brooklyn with Manhattan the structure is indicated only by the unobtrusive railing rising at a slight diagonal along the bottom of the canvas As opposed to focusing on the bridge that facilitates movement in and out of the city Hopper creates an image absent of noise or motion He emphasizes the alienation and anonymity of urban life by including a single figure a woman sitting alone in a top story window On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum edwardhopper fromwilliamsburgbridge williamsburgbridge americana

text: Marble statue of a wounded AmazonRoman imperial period st nd century A D Copy of a Greek bronze statue of ca B C Lower legs and feet have been restored with casts taken from copies in Berlin and Copenhagen Most of right arm lower part of pillar and plinth are eighteenth century marble restorations In Greek art the Amazons a mythical race of warrior women from Asia Minor were often depicted battling such heroes as Herakles Achilles and Theseus This statue represents a refugee from battle who has lost her weapons and bleeds from a wound under her right breast Her chiton is unfastened at one shoulder and belted at the waist with a makeshift bit of bridle from her horse Despite her plight her face shows no sign of pain or fatigue She leans lightly on a pillar at her left and rests her right arm gracefully on her head in a gesture often used to denote sleep or death Such emotional restraint was characteristic of classical art of the second half of the fifth century B C The original statue probably stood in the precinct of the great temple of Artemis at Ephesos on the coast of Asia Minor where the Amazons had legendary and cultic connections with the goddess The Roman writer Pliny the Elder described a competition held in the mid fifth century B C between five famous sculptors including Phidias Polykleitos and Kresilas who were to make a statue of an Amazon for the temple This type of statue is generally associated with that contest On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum sculpture amazon roman romanmythology greek greekmythology mythology pagan heathen lateantiquity

text: throwbackthursdayIt s not me but I m throwing back to I want to share with everyone a masterpiece of art This is called The Great Wave off Kanagawa or Kanagawa oki Nami Ura It is not a painting but a woodblock print This is from my native Japan and was created by ukiyo e artist Katsushika Hokusai Hokusai created a series called Thirty six Views of Mount Fuji This was the first in the series and his most famous work Mount Fuji is the tallest mountain and most sacred symbol of Japan The fierce blue wave complements the humble yet grand Mount Fuji hokusai katsushikahokusai ukiyoe japaneseart japaneseartist kanagawa japan mountfuji wave ocean woodblockprint art metropolitanmuseumofart losangelescountymuseumofart artinstituteofchicago britishmuseum nationalgalleryofvictoria claudemonethouse edo fisherman japanese bluewave tbt

text: Treasure Evening by the Lake Artist Max Nonnenbruch Where Private Collection Photo europe treasures Tag europe treasures Family tesori italiani contemporary treasures archaeology treasures Max Nonnenbruch was a German painter born in in Viersen A painter of genre scenes in his early days Max Nonnenbruch was then influenced by neoclassical and symbolist aesthetics as well as by pre Raphaelite painters His works represented young women dancers and odalisques with oriental dresses Many references to Greek and Roman antiquity can be seen Greek vases jewellery hairstyles columns and mosaic decorations The pure and idyllic scenes of Max Nonnenbruch were particularly visible in his works depicting young women dressed in antique at the seaside The vibrating touch highlights the effects of the lights Through his work and his involvement in the artistic events of his time Max Nonnenbruch acquired an important reputation Share our Wonderful Heritage art europeanart artists artwork german germany durer germanart deutsch musee artiste masterpiece kunst deutschland germania allemagne alemania museum alemanha maxnonnenbruch metropolitanmuseumofart d rer kunstwerke renaissance munich sunset gaertner

text: Marble head of a Greek generalRoman Imperial period st nd century A D Copy of a Greek bronze statue of the mid th century B C This powerful portrayal of a man of action belongs to a type popular in Roman times One suggestion for his identity is the strategos general Phokion pupil of Plato and one of the foremost Athenian statesmen of the fourth century B C but there is little evidence to support that theory We do not know if the original statue was a contemporary portrait like the famous fifth century portrait of the Athenian statesman and general Perikles or a posthumous work It could even be a representation of a hero from the mythic past He wears a Corinthian helmet pushed up and resting on the back of his head The helmet is elaborately decorated in relief with griffins on the bowl and rams heads on the cheek pieces and is similar to a type worn by the goddess Athena His eyes would have been inlaid in another material The head has been worked for insertion into a statue On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum scuplture romanempire roman greek athens phokion plato lateantiquity

text: Helmet Spangenhelm Iron copper alloy goldByzantine or Germanic th th centuryThis is one of the best preserved examples of a rare group of closely related Spangenhelme strap helmets dating from the sixth or seventh century The sites where they have been found are widely scattered ranging from Sweden to Germany the Balkans and Libya The quality of the helmets and their diverse locations lead to the theory that they were made as diplomatic gifts to foreign rulers perhaps sent from the Byzantine court or from the Ostrogothic kingdom in Italy Originally all the helmets had a pair of metal cheek pieces and a mail neck defense and often an integral nasal Of these features only the cheek pieces remain on a few examples This particular helmet is very unusual for its elaborate large scale figures engraved on the plates between the straps These include men birds fish and animals Featured is a cross above the brow indicating that the owner was probably a Christian On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum archaeology byzantine francia frankish carolingian migrationera migrationperiod viking vikings vikingage earlymedieval

text: Swords in Early JapanThe great burial mounds kofun of the Kofun period from about the late third to the late seventh century A D have yielded a wealth of richly decorated swords The earliest of these probably imported from China have straight single edged iron blades hilts with ring pommels and rudimentary guards and scabbards with mounts that allowed the weapon to hang from the belt at an angle Obtaining iron from Korea Japanese swordsmiths at first imitated these weapons so closely that it is extremely difficult to distinguish between the foreign originals and Japanese copies In the fifth or sixth century however new indigenous hilt types developed including one with a very large globular pommel Straight bladed jokot ancient swords are thought to have been used mainly for thrusting The curved blade that characterizes later swords Nippon t which were ideal for cutting seems to have developed in the late tenth century Top to bottom Sword with Scabbard MountsIron gilt copper silverProbably Japanese Kofun period th century Sword with Scabbard MountsIron gilt copper woodKofun period th century Sword with Scabbard MountsIron gilt copperKofun period th th century Sword with Scabbard MountsIron gilt bronze gilt copper silverKofun period th century Sword with Scabbard MountsIron gilt bronze silver woodChinese Sui Dynasty about Sword with Scabbard MountsIron gilt bronze silver woodChinese Sui Dynasty about Displayed at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan themet metropolitanmuseumofart sword jokoto nipponto tachi katana japan kofun kofunperiod asukaperiod yamatoperiod migrationera migrationperiod vikingage earlymedieval

text: I enjoy featuring artists whom I admire of which aligolkar is one of my all time favorites I have enjoyed both collecting his art and knowing him for nearly years I have spent nearly a lifetime studying art having traveled too numerous galleries around the world pausing in front of paintings sculptures and architecture and simply admiring the artists wonderful use of color medium or subject matter At times I have even been angered viewing the grotesque fallen human condition as it screams out at the viewer from the canvas Why for example do we require a painting of John the Baptist s head on a platter as can be viewed at the Getty Musuem in Malibu California As a sidenote These days there is a good bit of discussion about a recession As a disclaimer I am not a financial adviser That being said I believe there are a few exceptional living artists who are highly collectable as an investment to diversify ones portfolio In my opinion Ali Golkar is one of them Perhaps fifteen years ago over dinner Ali asked me what he could do to diversify Whereas before he only painted groupings of women I suggested he branch out and try other venues such as landscapes seascapes and still lifes As you can see here Ali did just that I also suggested that he place his art in Martin Lawrence Galleries There are several locations throughout the country Ali was immediately picked up by Martin Lawrence I was delighted to stroll through Soho in New York and chance upon one of his large landscapes in the window You can admire his work at aligolkar com aligolkar collectableartists text: Folio from a Qur an ManuscriptSyria Damascus second half of the th centuryInk opaque watercolor and gold on parchment This large folio is attributed to the very early Abbasid period making it one of the earliest datable Qur an leaves in the collection On each of its sides are sixteen lines of kufic script executed in brownish black ink with vowels indicated in red and green dots Like many early Qur an folios it is written on parchment and exhibits extensive elongation of the letters along a horizontal axis The latter was a response to the vertical page format characteristic of kufic Qur ans and a decorative device that resulted in a stunning composition The text is from sura verses through On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum middleeast levant damascus syria islam islamicart quran koran kufic arabic abbasidcaliphate vikingage earlymedieval

text: Egypt Syria and the Jazira From the tenth to twelfth centuries the area including present day Algeria Tunisia Sicily Egypt and Syria came under the rule of the Fatimid dynasty which traced descent from the Prophet Muhammad s daughter Fatima and from Isma il the seventh Shi i imam In the Fatimids established Cairo as a new capital It soon rivaled Abbasid Baghdad in wealth and power Meanwhile the Seljuq dynasty after conquering Baghdad in set its sights westward bringing Anatolia under its control after Based in Konya Seljuq power in Anatolia reached its zenith in the first half of the thirteenth century In the Jazira the region between the northern Euphrates and the Tigris and northern Syria local regimes emerged prominent among them were the Artuqids and the Zangids In Egypt the Ayyubid dynasty came to power under the Zangid general Salah al Din known in Europe as Saladin al Ayyubi He established himself as sultan and soon expanded his control to Yemen Syria and the Jazira Despite conquering Jerusalem in the Ayyubid conflict with the Crusaders continued To face this challenge the Ayyubids built an army largely of slave soldiers mamluks who ultimately overthrew the last Ayyubid sultan in Egypt and founded the Mamluk sultanate RingEgypt Fatimid period th centuryGold filigree and granulation Biconical Bead with ScrollsSyria Fatimid period th centuryGold filigree and granulation Spherical BeadEgypt or Syria Fatimid period th centuryGold filigree and granulation Crescent shaped Pendant with Confronted BirdsEgypt Fatimid period th centuryGold cloisonn enamel turquoise filigree Pair of EarringsSyria Fatimid period th centuryGold filigree and granulation On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum archaeology middleeast levant syria egypt fatimidcaliphate islam islamicart vikingage

text: Nasal HelmetSteel copper alloyWeight lb oz g European about Although nasal helmets a type that covers the top of the head with a bar extending down from the brow to protect the nose were widely used in medieval Europe this is one of only a handful that survive today This example is also distinguished by the remains of intricate interlace designs delicately inlaid in copper wire that form a Christian cross on its brow and nasal Shirt of MailSteel copper alloy iron brassWeight lb g German Nuremberg about The brass seal on the chest includes the name and emblem of the city of Nuremberg a famous center of armor manufacturing SwordSteel copper alloyWeight lb oz g European possibly German about SDSIS and DSR are inlaid in copper alloy on either side of the blade SwordSteel silver wood leatherWeight lb oz g European about SwordSteel copper alloyWeight lb oz g European about The pommel of this sword is inlaid with a cross and the blade with the letters INCDISI SwordSteel woodWeight lb oz g European possibly Italian about SwordSteel copper alloyWeight lb oz g European about SwordSteel silver goldWeight lb oz g German about Although damaged and missing its guard this blade is important for its surface color and finish and for the long enigmatic inscription inlaid on each side in fine gold and silver wire Pair of StirrupsIron bronze gold silverScandinavian possibly Danish about On display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art artmuseum archaeology vikingage earlymedieval highmiddleages nasalhelm vikinghelm sword vikingsword chainmail nuremberg germany italy denmark

text: Why Double Coated Dogs Should Not be ShavedWhen deciding whether or not to shave your dog you need to determine what kind of coat your dog has single or double Double coated breeds are those that have two layers of fur The top layer is made of tough guard hairs and the bottom layer is a thick layer of fur called an undercoat The undercoat is a layer of fine hairs close to an animals skin that help keep them cool in the summer and warm in winter In the spring they go through a major shedding period known as blowing their coat when much of that undercoat is released to make way for their lighter summer coat Common double coated breeds include Huskies Chows Labradors German Shepherds Golden Retrievers and Pomeranian s Most of the herding breeds have a double coat as well as the Spitz type breeds and a majority of Terriers Shop The Pish Pad Store For Top Quality Pet Products Visit Chrisman Couture on Etsy chrismanmaltese chrismancouture maltese maltesepuppy maltesepuppylove www thepishpadstore com showpremiumpetgroomingproducts metropolitanmuseumofart Chihuahua teacupyorkie teacuppuppy teacuppoodle puppies husbandhusband gaycouple gaybusiness luxurylifestyle dogfashion doggrooming doggroomer gay gayboy facebookads richandfamous showpremiumpetgroomingproducts metropolitanmuseumofart Chihuahua teacupyorkie teacuppuppy teacuppoodle puppies husbandhusband gaycouple gaybusiness luxurylifestyle dogfashion doggrooming doggroomer gay gayboy facebookads furcoat maltese maltesepuppy malteselove malteseforsale toydog richandfamous showpremiumpetgroomingproducts metropolitanmuseumofart Chihuahua teacupyorkie teacuppuppy teacuppoodle puppies husbandhusband gaycouple gaybusiness luxurylifestyle dogfashion doggrooming doggroomer gay gayboy facebookads

text: Yesterday morning we started our day in upper Manhattan by eating NY bagels from the very popular Pick a Bagel did not disappoint They have everything from vegan spreads to classic lox jalape o and strawberry walnut delish We then walked up to Central Park to explore some of the famous sights within the park We hit up the Carousel the Bethesda Fountain the Market the Loeb Boathouse the Belvedere Castle and the Shakespeare Garden Central Park is truly a little oasis within the city After we left the park we ventured off into museum world by going by the Metropolitan Museum of Art and touring the Guggenheim There is something magical about the art scene in NYC than only experiencing it can express Before we ended our time in the upper part of the city we walked down Park Ave looking at the well known windows of Bergdorf Goodman They are unmatched in their visual design capabilities So very cool I swear I walked right by Martha Stewart I looked deep into her eyes to verify it was her lol Although Christopher does not agree with my identification of Martha centralpark pickabagel museums metropolitanmuseumofart guggenheim bergdorfgoodman travel thebelvederecastle

text: Here s another jewel from the met museum of art that Kimberly and I viewed on our recent visit to New York Robert Blum was an illustrator hired by Scribner s Magazine He was able to spend eighteen months in Japan and the details in this painting show how deeply he was able to immerse himself in the culture over that time period This is not a large painting x and yet Blum is able to add an extreme level of detail With the various patterns throughout the painting the frame itself adds to the chaotic nature of the scene The way Blum handled the patterns in the fabric is breathtaking It s also important to note that he used red on the foreground figure which makes it pop right out at the viewer juxtaposed against the more muted colors surrounding it and adds a further sense of depth to the painting The candy blower becomes the center of interest due to the value contrast and rich color in his clothing and also the fact that so many of the other figures are focused on his actions I m personally intrigued by the block letter on the crate It makes the scene appear to be almost a hybrid of the historical and the modern Japan The Ameya A Japanese Candy Vendor Robert Blum Oil on Canvas x Photos by Kimberly at saundersfinearts

text: Pieter Bruegel the Elder The Harvesters oil on wood cm cm Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City Bruegel s fanfare for the common man is considered one of the defining works of Western art This composition was one of six created on the theme of the seasons The time is probably early September A group of peasants on the left cut and bundle ripened wheat while the on the right another group takes their midday meal One figure is sacked out under a tree with his pants unbuttoned This attention to detail continues throughout the painting as a procession of ever granular observations receding into space It was extraordinary for a time when landscapes served mostly as backdrops for religious paintings Do you like this painting

text: Distorted Balthasar Permoser German Marsyas ca Marble on a black marble socle inlaid with light marble panels The Metropolitan Museum of Art New York In one of the great parables of hubris the satyr Marsyas challenged the god Apollo to a musical competition The god triumphed and then punished his challenger by skinning him alive Here Permoser condensed the tragic climax of the story into an emotive portrayal of Marsyas The contorted face with an open mouth revealing a bitten tongue and twisting head immediately convey pain while the taut shoulders suggest that his arms are bound behind his back The satyr is draped with an animal pelt pointing to his gruesome fate The panels of mottled marble set into the base are flecked with red perhaps evoking spattered blood It s difficult for me to walk past and not stop and gasp every time AliceSchwarz Marsyas BalthasarPermoser metmuseum sculpture nycart nycmuseums museums metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart met metnyc marble sculpture museums metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart metnyc sculpture sculptures artsculptures marblesculptures sculptures museos museums artmuseums museumstagram nycmuseums girlsinmuseums peopleinmuseums museumspaces museumspass museumoftheworld museumstag museumspassambassador museumholic museumholics

text: After all deadlines and chaos memories from New York One of my favorite painter Jackson Pollock thanks to him American painting freed itself from European dependencies and took over the leading position Master of action painting quick gesture painting on canvas flat laid on the floor in the studio In this way he became a part of it he could work around canvas go inside Often commented that everyone could create something like this something so jerky accidental and instinctive However looking at his entire work can be seen in this well thought out workshop I thought for a long time that his painting is the result of alcohol intoxication However the truth is that he always painted on an empty stomach He drank a lot but then he fell into depressive states and then did not create Expelled from Manual School in Los Angeles for his rebellious nature today is a symbol of American art an icon of contemporary art In the s the art of American Indians and the frescoes of Mexican artists strongly influenced him Pollock s sketchbooks have survived which testify to his proficiency in classical drawing which confirms the theory that the great masters before they start to experiment in their style often destroying the current order the previous style they first master the classic drawing It was not until that he began to paint abstract paintings permeated by violent expressionism Pollock dies in a car accident in Pollock s painting was one of the most important phenomena in th century art pollock jacksonpollock jacksonpollock momanewyork moma newyork met metropolitanmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart metropolitanmuseumnewyork guggenheimcollection peggyguggenheimcollection guggenheimcollection guggenheimmuseum modernart actionpainting actionpaintings contemporaryart contemporarypainting newyork

text: Chamunda the Horrific Destroyer of Evil This is a fragment of a full length sculpture portraying the ferocious Hindu goddess Kali in the form of Chamunda an epithet derived from her act of decapitating the demons Chanda and Munda Chamunda embodies bareness and decay Her hair is piled up into a chignon decorated with a tiara of skulls and a crescent moon She scowls baring her teeth and enormous eyeballs protrude menacingly from sunken sockets in her skeletal face As a necklace she wears a snake whose coils echo the rings of decaying flesh that sag beneath her collarbone Just above her navel on her emaciated torso is a scorpion a symbol of sickness and death She presumably once held lethal objects in the hands of her twelve missing arms Chamunda is naked except for a short diaphanous dhoti partially covering the two tiger skins complete with heads that hang from her waist to her knees Although her extremities are missing it is clear from comparison with related images that this Chamunda stood with legs straight the right turned outward The starkness and uncompromising horror of this sculpture are representative of one aspect of Indian theology Like images of Shiva in his dark form of Bhairava such macabre images of the Goddess are common occupants of the exterior walls of temples They appear both on shrines dedicated to Shiva and those to the Goddess herself metmuseum Chamunda the Horrific Destroyer of Evil Made in India th th century Sandstone Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum Ch mund l horrible destructrice du mal Produite en Inde X me XI me si cle Gr s Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum th post of DailyMuseum This week Art of India

text: The Love Letter Jean Honor Franogard What I find so fascinating about this work is not only the teasing expression on the woman s face but also the use of colour Here we see touches of colour only where the light streams in the soft touches of blue and pink The rest of the painting is a monotone and brown This mirrors the way we view the world the cones in our eyes pick up on colour but can only do so in light

text: SLIT GONG Papua New Guinea Korewori River middle Sepik region Yimam peoples th or early th century wood In many parts of New Guinea the sounds produced by certain types of musical instruments played during ceremonies are said to be the voices of ancestors or supernatural beings In Sepik cultures the most important instruments are sacred flutes and slit gongs Slit gongs are percussion instruments hollowed from logs to create a chamber with a narrow slit like aperture the edges of the slit are struck with wood beaters to create resonant tones and complex rhythms Slit gongs are a prominent feature of men s ceremonial houses where they are arranged on the earthen floor of the open structure Although played exclusively by men they are relatively public objects visible at least on certain occasions to the community at large Others forms of ritual instruments are strictly secret and hidden from women children and uninitiated men themet themetropolitan metropolitanmuseumofarts metropolitanmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart metropolitanmuseumnewyork newguinea papuanewguinea papanewguinea papua papuaindonesia slit slitgong carranca carrancas sepik sepikculture percussion musicalinstruments mylife bestdays best vibes myday

name: 2019-08-21 22.16.20 2115383455429535483_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: AMBRYM SLIT GONGS The towering slit gongs of Northern Vanuatu are among the largest freestanding musical instruments on earth Found primarily on Ambrym Malakula and neighboring islands they are carved from the trunks of large breadfruit trees hollowed out to create a resonating chamber with a narrow slit shaped aperture The edges of the slit are struck with club like wood beaters producing deep sonorous tones A number of gongs constituting an informal orchestra stand on the Village s dancing ground These gongs orchestras are played at major social and ceremonial occasions such as initiations dances and funerals Through carefully coordinated actions the drummers in the gong ensemble produce rhythms of immense variety and complexity Slit gongs are or were used to communicate between villages Under proper atmospheric conditions their sound can carry for miles through the forest and in rare instances across the water to neighboring islands A series of gong languages composed of beats and pauses enables highly specific messages to be sent The slit gong and finials exhibited here are from Ambrym island The complete gong from Fanla Village was commissioned in the s by the village chief Tain Mai Who was acknowledged as its creator but it was carved by Tin Mweleun an artist from a neighboring village The gong is made in the form of a stylized ancestor figure The spiral motifs painted on the eyes represent Metan Galgal the morning star Small arms and spirals depicting sacred pig tusks appear on either side of the face which is surrounded by projections representing hair The long vertical slit represents the mouth through which the ancestor s voice emerges as sound whenever the gong is played themet themetropolitan metropolitanmuseumofarts text: Kwakwaka wakw Kwakiutl Female Figure Canada British Columbia th century wood paint Lives in the Arts of Africa Oceania and the Americas at the Metropolitan Museum of Art metmuseum The carving traditions of Northwest Coast peoples are very strong and of uncertain age The traditions were well established when Europeans arrived in the late eighteenth century and are continued today The expressive ceremonial life of Native peoples enriches their carving as it enriches all communal activities Complex and imaginative mythological themes were rendered three dimensionally In terms of the scale and presence of wood sculpture no group surpassed the Kwakwaka wakw Kwakiutl of Queen Charlotte Strait in central British Columbia By the late nineteenth century freestanding Kwakwaka wakw totem poles were big and tall and deeply carved This unusual female figure may have been part of such a pole or of an interior house post It is flattened in back as if to fit against a support The position of the figure s hands implies a sexually derived theme perhaps one that refers to specific reasons Remnants of a pattern in red appear on her face most extensively on the chin and on the long braids are remains of black paint Text source metmuseum wall text themet metropolitanmuseumofart kwakwakawakw kwakiutl femalefigure canadabritishcolumbia britishcolumbia native thcentury artsofafricaoceaniaandtheamericas africaoceaniaamericas woodcarving carving woodsculpture sculpture queencharlottestrait totempoles ny nyc art artmuseum museum

text: Time to revisit my version of the Three Graces original statue on display at metmuseum These young girls linked in a dance like pose represent The Three Graces Aglaia Beauty Euphrosyne Mirth and Thalia Abundance They bestow what is most pleasurable and beneficent in nature and society fertility and growth beauty in the arts harmonious reciprocity between men They enjoyed venerable cults in Greece and Asia Minor In mythology they play an attendant role gracing festivals and organizing dances Their closest connection is with Aphrodite whom they serve as handmaidens This carefully calculated frieze like composition is typical of classicizing art of the second and first centuries B C Instantly recognizable it soon became the canonic formula for representing the Graces who appeared in every medium and on every kind of object from mirrors to sarcophagi chicago chicagoart chicagoartist jasonbranson JasonBransonDotCom redmonks art drawing artist threegraces statue themet metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart nyc newyork

text: ELIZABETH MURRAY Children Meeting whitneymuseum Art is an epiphany in a coffee cup Elizabeth Murray If I had to describe Elizabeth Murray s work with one word I d keep it simple and say Fun Her colorful cartoonish style breathed life back into painting at a time when people thought the medium was dying But Murray s delightful compositions were equally as serious as they were fun Murray s work broke with artistic conventions and later in her life frankly acknowledged her own mortality and illness But even as her art became more serious Murray held onto her iconic playful style I love this painting in particular because of the way it achieves the sensation of children playing without any figuration Like Brancusi s Bird in Flight we can perceive the subject matter without actually seeing it All it takes is some bright colors eclectic shapes and a sense of movement While it may sometimes feel like you need a PhD to understand artists talking Murray kept her descriptions playful and the simple using words like goofy silly and wacky This playfulness is exactly what I love about Murray she didn t take art so seriously Murray made painting fun pushing back against the austerity of previous generations of artists It wasn t all fun and games though Murray also contributed to the historical canon with her multi panel compositions that literally stretched the boundaries of painting Like a jigsaw puzzle she would piece together dozens of oddly shaped canvases to make sprawling colorful compositions While other artists such as Ellsworth Kelly pioneered the shaped canvas Murray took the practice to its apotheosis This painting from the Whitney was actually made before Murray developed her signature style there s only one canvas but the MoMA has the of the great examples of her puzzle like technique and it would be worth checking out when the museum re opens in October

text: Gruppo statuario delle Tre Grazie Metropolitan Museum of Art New York Le Cariti divinit dell antica Grecia dette dai Romani Gratiae sono personificazioni della grazia e della bellezza e loro dispensatrici Secondo la mitologia greca sono figlie di Zeus e di Eurinome I loro nomi sono Aglaia Bellezza Eufrosine Gioia Talia Abbondanza Esse erano le ancelle di Afrodite e in questo gruppo scultoreo sono raffigurate come fanciulle nude in una posa armoniosa dalla composizione simile a quella di un fregio Di questa scultura non si conosce n la provenienza n l autore Si tratta sicuramente di una copia romana di II sec d C di un originale risalente al tardo periodo ellenistico Tale scultura era forse collocata originariamente in un giardino o in un bagno pubblico Statuary group of the Three Graces Metropolitan Museum of Art New York The Charites goddes of ancient Greece known as the Roman Gratiae are personifications and bestowers of grace and beauty According to the Greek mythology they are daughters of Zeus and Eurinome Their names are Aglaea Beauty Euphrosyne Joy Thalia Abundance They were the handmaids of Aphrodite and in this sculptural group they are depicted as naked girls in a harmonious pose with a composition similar to that of a frieze Neither the origin nor the author is known of this sculpture It is certainly a Roman copy of the second century AD of an original dating back to the late Hellenistic period This sculpture was perhaps originally placed in a garden or in a public bath Photo by vif america metropolitanmuseumofart newyork newyorkcity nyc met metnyc tregrazie threegraces graces sculpture romansculpture romanart statue museum museo history culture ancientart greekmithology mithology art arteantica archeology antiquities museo archeology antiqua archeologia heritage worldheritage

text: Untitled Lithograph by SirTerryFrost British Artist proof Signed by the artist in pencil Sir Terry Frost was an English painter known for his geometric abstractions and color studies that spanned over decades Frost was born in the U K He served in the Second World War and was captured by the Nazi s as a prisoner of war After his release and return to England Frost attended the Camberwell School of Art and studied under Ben Nicholson and William Coldstream Frost exhibited worldwide and later taught at the University of Leeds and the University of Reading In he was elected to the Royal Academy and knighted in In a major retrospective of Frost s work was held at the Royal Academy of Arts in London Frost s work can be found at the Tate Gallery in London Metropolitan Museum of Art and the National Galleries of Scotland in Edinburgh among others

text: My next stop was NYC to visit the Metropolitan Museum of Art I was particularly interested to visit the collections of Ancient Near East and the Islamic Art Today I will share with you a few highlights from the Ancient Near Eastern collections The statue one of my favorite artworks of the ancient world is of Gudea who ruled Lagash between and BCE and ordered a series of diorite statues displaying him as an ultimate pious ruler The next photo is of a th century BCE Achaemenid rhyton in the shape of a leonid beast showcasing the technical skills of Persian metalworkers The next photo shows three Sasanian silver vessels one of the best known objects from Sasanian Iran Many of these vessels display a scene in which a Sasanian king identified by his specific crown is hunting wild animals You can see the details of two of these pieces in the following pictures I am extremely grateful to Dr Henry Colburn seen in the last photo an amazing scholar of ancient Near Eastern art who kindly hosted me during my two visits to the museum and made the arrangements for my visit to the special collections smuarthistory smumeadows meadows arthistory NYC MetropolitanMuseumofArt

text: Metropolitan Museum of Art s metmuseum ongoing exhibition titled Sita and Rama The Ramayana in Indian Painting displays one of the epic narratives of South Asian Literature through a collection of paintings These have been made by court artists from the th and th centuries for the Rajput and Pahari courts of north India The artworks are on display from August to February and again from February to August making it a year long exhibition The chosen artworks offer strong visual illustrations of this Sanskrit epic and encompass its various facets effectively through two mediums Some of the textiles are huge and the massive scale suggests that they were meant to be seen by large audiences In contrast the paintings would have been viewed by individuals or small groups In this sense the paintings often show a single event and relate closely to the text of the Ramayana The textiles present major characters and climatic moments such as the final battle between Rama and Ravana Together these two media work well to beautifully tell the story and to emphasise the diversity of the Indian painting and textile traditions shares Kurt Behrendt Associate Curator in the Department of Asian Art at the Met who has organised this exhibition linkinbio Photography Rumal with Scenes from the Ramayana India Jammu and Kashmir Chamba th century Cotton with silk tinsel and metal embroidery The Metropolitan Museum of Art Rogers Fund Writer Avni Raut

text: Credit to from europe treasures get regrann Treasure Artemis Artist Max Nonnenbruch Where Private Collection Photo christiesinc Tag europe treasures Family tesori italiani contemporary treasures archaeology treasures Max Nonnenbruch was a German painter born in in Viersen A painter of genre scenes in his early days Max Nonnenbruch was then influenced by neoclassical and symbolist aesthetics as well as by pre Raphaelite painters His works represented young women dancers and odalisques with oriental dresses Many references to Greek and Roman antiquity can be seen Greek vases jewellery hairstyles columns and mosaic decorations The pure and idyllic scenes of Max Nonnenbruch were particularly visible in his works depicting young women dressed in antique at the seaside The vibrating touch highlights the effects of the lights Through his work and his involvement in the artistic events of his time Max Nonnenbruch acquired an important reputation Share our Wonderful Heritage art europeanart artists artwork german germany durer germanart deutsch musee artiste masterpiece kunst metropolitanmuseumofart d rer kunstwerke renaissance privatecollection finearts repost art artlover instagood regrann

name: 2019-08-23 07.16.41 2116380192424299181_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Today I bring you some of the highlights from the Islamic galleries at the Metropolitan Museum of Art The first picture is from the Sharmin and Bijan Mossavar Rahmani gallery dedicated to Safavid and Later Persian Art followed by a close up of one of the several carpets adorning the room a fine th century Safavid carpet known as the Seley carpet The following pictures are highlights from several galleries of the Islamic art collections at the Met A group of cosmetic flasks dated to th th century designed to hold kohl a black cosmetic powder applied around the eyes A fine Seljuq luster ceramic of Kashan depicting a wedding procession A th th century minai enameled ware depicting the story of Bahram Gur and Azadeh which also is the motif of a th century Sasanian silver vessel posted yesterday And finally one of the most impressive pieces at the Met a th century gilded minai ware In this rare group of ceramics Medieval Muslim potters boasted their technological and artistic prowess by combining two unique technics of minai painting and gilding to create such masterpieces smuarthistory smumeadows meadows MetropolitanMuseumofArt

text: MARK ROTHKO No metmuseum Silence is so accurate Rothko WroteAccurate like an arrow without a targetand no target in mind Silence has its own roar or not roar just as Rothko wrote I don t express myself in my paintings I express my not self A poem that expresses the not self Everything but the self The meadow s veil of fog but is veil self referential Already dawn the not birds alert to what silence has to offer The fog one of Rothko s shapes hanging there in the not self humming Mikel before he died loved Rothko most When he could still think he put his mind to those sorts of judgments If I pull the fog away like theater curtains what then Sadness shapes the landscape The arrow of myself thwacks the nearest tree Fog steps closer like a perpetrator or a god Oh I m weeping Tears feed the silence like a mother drops into her baby not bird s open beaksome sweet but dangerous morsel DIANE SEUSS Silence Is so Accurate

text: Empress Dagmar by Ivan Kramskoi In tzarevich Nicholas became betrothed to Dagmar On April he died from meningitis His last wish was that Dagmar would marry his younger brother the future Alexander III In her father in law Alexander II of Russia was killed by a bomb In her diary Maria later described how the wounded still living Emperor was taken to the palace His legs were crushed terribly and ripped open to the knee a bleeding mass with half a boot on the right foot and only the sole of the foot remaining on the left Alexander II died a few hours later and Maria became tzarina Maria is described as a success in her social role as Empress loved to dance at the balls of high society and became a popular socialite and hostess of the Imperial balls her daughter Olga commented Court life had to run in splendor and there my mother played her part without a single false step After the Bolshevic revolution and the murder of her son Nicholas II she writes in her diary I am sure they all got out of Russia and now the Bolsheviks are trying to hide the truth She firmly held on to this conviction until her death The truth was too painful for her to admit publicly Her letters to her son and his family have since almost all been lost but in one that survives she wrote to Nicholas You know that my thoughts and prayers never leave you I think of you day and night and sometimes feel so sick at heart that I believe I cannot bear it any longer But God is merciful He will give us strength for this terrible ordeal Maria s daughter Olga Alexandrovna commented further on the matter Yet I am sure that deep in her heart my mother had steeled herself to accept the truth some years before her death drawing met metropolitanmuseumofart louvre hermitage oldmasters canvas text: Celestial dancer Devata The Hindu temple is conceived as a heavenly abode for the presiding deity The building s stepped indented and towering exterior evokes the mountains of Indra s heavens home to the assembly of gods as well as celestial beauties dancers and musicians This life size sandstone sculpture is an extraordinary rending of a heavenly celebrant performing in honor of the gods The dancer s face and body are treated according to prescribed canons of beauty Her body is contorted in an improbably pose her legs projecting to her right while her upper torso and head turn sharply left The extreme flexion reflects dance positions karunas and sthanas described in the Natyasastra an ancient dramatic arts treatise It is understood in Indian aesthetics that such positions enhance the appreciation of beauty metmuseum Celestial dancer Devata Made in Central India Madhya Pradesh mid th century Chandela period Sandstone Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum Danseuse c leste Devata R alis dans le centre de l Inde Madhya Pradesh Milieu du XI me si cle Gr s Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum th post of DailyMuseum This week Art of India

text: ankh In Hinduism the conch shell is usually associated with the god Vishnu Lord of the Waters but the brass fittings on this shell indicate a link with Shaivite ritual The mouthpiece suggests a lotus while the heavily decorated conical end depicts rows of nagas serpent divinities and wreath bearing kirtimukhas Faces of Glory A yoni design symbol of female energy is interspersed between each naga and kirtimukha The fitting terminates with the head of a makara elephant crocodile monster atop which strides a yali elephant lion monster Three figures rest at the upper edge of the shell s opening the lingam yoni symbol of Shiva and representation of the unified male female force Ganesh the elephant headed son of Shiva and Nandi a milk white bull who serves as Shiva s vehicle The opening of the hoofed stand represents a yoni metmuseum ankh Made in the Kerala State southwestern Malabar Coast of India th century Shell Turbinella pyrum brass wax Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum ankh R alis dans l Etat indien du Kerala XIX me si cle Coquillage Turbinella pyrum laiton et cire Metropolitan Museum of Art New York metmuseum th post of DailyMuseum This week Art of India

text: A lesser known painting by my favorite artist Edouard Manet Manet s model Victorine Meurent had recently posed as the brazen nudes in Olympia and Luncheon on the Grass both Mus e d Orsay Paris Here appearing relatively demure she flaunts an intimate silk dressing gown Critics eyed the painting as a rejoinder to Courbet s Woman with a Parrot and as indicative of Manet s current vice of failing to value a head more than a slipper Recent scholars have interpreted it as an allegory of the five senses the nosegay smell the orange taste the parrot confidant hearing and the man s monocle she fingers sight and touch manet metropolitanmuseumofart art impressionism painting olympia modeling

text: Tesoro Salom con la testa di San Giovanni Battista d C Artista Andrea Solario Luogo NewYork Metropolitan MuseumFoto metmuseumTag tesori italiani Family europe treasures contemporary treasures archaeology treasures Salom con la testa di San Giovanni Battista un dipinto del pittore milanese Andrea Solario Del dipinto esistono pi versioni questa al Metropolitan Museum senz altro la pi bella e fu realizzata per un nobile committente in Francia dove Solario lavor intorno al Realizzata con un incredibile attenzione per i dettagli l artista ha raggiunto un effetto impressionante giocando sul contrasto tra la bellezza e i gioielli intricati di Salom e l orribile vista della testa del Battista tenuta in mano dal braccio del carnefice Il naturalismo descrittivo dei riflessi e delle superfici debitore sia a Leonardo Da Vinci che per decenni lavor a Milano sia alla pittura olandese Salome with the Head of Saint John the Baptist is the finest of several versions of this composition painted by the Milanese artist and may have been painted for a noble patron in France where Solario worked from about Carried out with incredible attention to detail the artist achieved a striking effect by contrasting Salome s idealized beauty and jewels with the horrific view of the Baptist s head held by the cropped arm of the executioner The descriptive naturalism of reflections and surface textures is indebted to both Leonardo who worked for decades in Milan and Netherlandish painting italia beniculturali italianpainter peinture painter metropolitanmuseumofart ig art italy italianart renaissance andreasolario rinascimento metropolitanmuseum usa kunst musee metmuseum volgoarte museum museo

text: There was a bus stop outside my apartment Everyday i took a private bus cheaper and not as well kept as public to Manhattan I didn t care who the stranger sat next to me was I didnt care who saw me or if i looked too upscale for this not so expensive bus I didnt worry about my uber driver taking a turn down a dark road or him staring at me with hungry eyes through the rear view mirror I didnt care that i was walking alone in Times Square at am I didnt care about what i wore I didnt care what people thought of me I didnt feel uncomfortable in my own body I didnt feel like my gender was a free ticket to stare me up and down lane I didnt feel like a helpless prey open for predators to look at to undress with their eyes I felt free I felt liberated I felt independent I felt like there wasn t anything I couldn t do on my own Then i realisedThis is what men feel like all the time fashionblog pinkblob formaldresses themet priyankachopra beautyblogger makeupartist womenempowerment womenhelpingwomen goalsmakeup fashion styleinspo styleblogger nyc nycmuseums metropolitanmuseumofart liberation

text: What does a can of tomato soup have in common with fashion The answer an artist s eye One needs to be insane to a degree to have a different prospective in order to be able to create something others never even thought of before You have the last chance to discover CAMP at The Costume Institute s exhibition Camp Notes on Fashion on view through September at The Metropolitan Museum of Art NewYork Camp s disruptive nature and subversion of modern aesthetic values has often been trivialized but this exhibition reveals that it has had a profound influence on both high art and popular culture said Max Hollein Director of The Met By tracing its evolution and highlighting its defining elements the show embodies the ironic sensibilities of this audacious style challenges conventional understandings of beauty and taste and establishes the critical role that this important genre has played in the history of art and fashion Camp dandyism in the age of mass culture makes no distinction between the unique object and the mass produced object as is shown in a Warhol Campbell s tomato soup print and a minidress made of the same pattern You don t have to fully understand camp to enjoy the show but it s worth trying fashion art gallery gucci campnotesonfashion notesonfashion collection design artist inspiration creation visual newyork metropolitanmuseumofart andywarholart andywarhol popart campbellssoup canoftomatosoup dress exhibition provocation bespoke clothing

text: Romance and passion sizzle in the summer natsu t t bist n Persian The season of love growth joy vitality fullness youthfulness and the main period of vegetation growth Life is an open book and adventures abound A season of vacation holidays and when children are out of school Characterized by noisy and annoying insects and with the blistering sun providing warmth In literature summer often coincides with the prime of a protagonist s life overcoming challenges to build character and an occasional ritual death Shakespeare equated summer with beauty and youth Fertility love and ambiguous sexuality are major themes in his play Midsummer Night s Dream Mendelssohn who composed the music for the play made extensive use of violins and symphonic bombasts The composer s famous recessional Wedding March served as incidental music for this play If summer had one defining scent it d definitely be the smell of barbecue Katie Lee

text: We are lovers curators and educators of sneakers fashion art and culture Every week we feature a staff pick of something we love outside of our normal stream of commerce Several RuleofNext Team Members were onsite the Grand Opening of the District Art Gallery a sophisticated modern environment that provides art enthusiasts established and new collectors decorators and browsers with an unrivaled visual art experience district gallery An evening to remember hundreds gathered in celebration to the Van Aken District s new addition to the community and were delightfully welcomed with food music drink and a sleek modernistic atmosphere pleasantly housed within high ceilings snd elegantly textured floors The District Art Gallery is home to both national and international art exhibits and represents emerging established and mid career level artists in addition to providing consultation installation framing and art curation services Fostering relationships between art dealers and buyer engaging through the local community through partnership opportunities and education are among the initiatives the District Art Gallery has sought out to accomplish Committed to bringing world renown art and artists with providing opportunities for emerging artists the District Art Gallery brings hope culture and possibility to the community for what we hope to be for a very long time For more information on art and other inquiries visit https district gallery com districtgalleryart We hope you are having a great weekend Rule of Next Staff

text: FINALLY posting this one even though I ve finished the book well over two weeks ago and took this first picture on my birthday nearly a month ago is simply stated my favorite novel and no words seemed right to convey the whole background story SO I ll try and keep this succinct First off a massive thank you to coffeeandaclassic for still having boxes available in your Etsy shop The beanie and pint glass are amazing The whole box was beautifully organized and I could not be happier with it Second the criterion release of is stupendous and well worth viewing and buying eric charles and team did a masterful job restoring it to its totalitarian glory Third yes I did get a tattoo on my foot Done wonderfully by christianmasot Highly recommend him if you are looking to get work done in the Jersey City area Sorry the pic is crappy but it is still healing Finally the actual book pic was taken at metropolitanmuseumofart on my birthday May seem an odd place to read but they have all these cool places that are perfect for relaxing and taking in the art work Plus it was weirdly fitting to read about a government that destroys the past when you are in a place that is all about the past If you haven t read this one I cannot recommend or nag you enough to This is one of those books that is terrifyingly relevant Thanks for reading my ramble if you got this far igreads orwell booktattoo bookphotography coffeandclassics bookworm booksofinstagram

text: Egyptian Middle Kingdom th Dynasty c BC Hippopotamus William faience x x in coll Metropolitan Museum of Art NY I ll wager this is one of the most popular objects in the Met s collection When I was there the other day I overheard a Japanese tourist asking a guard where William was the guard immediately pointed him to this The nickname was first used in a Punch the British humor magazine and it stuck No doubt modern eyes find him adorable but for Egyptians he was a large and dangerous beast Three of his legs are restored they were probably intentionally broken when he was placed in the tomb presumably that of steward Senbi so that he would not be able to hurt the deceased Even knowing that I find it hard to see William as anything but charming egyptiansculpture faience hippopotamus hippopotamuswilliam metropolitanmuseumofart middlekingdom thdynasty egyptian

text: The artist Alicja Kwade s ParaPivot a foot tall illusionistic sculpture installed atop the Metropolitan Museum of Art is on view through October Nine marbled spheres some of which weigh more than a ton sit suspended among a series of interlocking steel frames The spheres give off an uneasy feeling appearing to be both frozen in a gravity defying moment and capable of falling on you at any moment Like the nine planets they symbolize the stones each have a different look composition and backstory One is made of azul macaubas sourced from Brazil another comes from materials found in Norway We re all playing this game Kwade said Everyday things seem so important But then you zoom out and realize that you re standing with another billion people on a spinning sphere With that perspective she says you re reminded to just be glad you re here at all

text: Me qued con tantas ganas de compartirles cosas sobre el arte despu s del video que hice para fargstudio Asique voy a compartirles un par Por un lado c mo encarar un museo cuando uno viaja qu puede haber en un museo y c mo saber a donde ir y adem s qu hacer frente a una obra de arte para disfrutarla y empezar a entenderla Para esto ltimo les dejo un par de consejos comentarios Contexto intenten entender el contexto en que la obra fue pintada El contexto es important simo porque nos sit a en todas las problem ticas del momento en que el artista elige pintar su obra Nos ayuda a entender qu estaba viviendo el artista y en relaci n a esto por qu su obra termin siendo importante en la historia del arte T cnica y materiales esta es la parte maravillosa que uno se puede quedar mirando y explorando por un rato largo Ac rquense vean las pinceladas los colores la textura qu eligi y junto con el contexto sit ense en el lugar del artista tal vez hace o a os pintando esta obra que hoy est n mirando ustedes No les parece fascinante Las obras de arte son una combinaci n de tantas cosas fascinantes un momento en la historia una problem tica una cultura creatividad lo que quiso transmitir el artista c mo lo termin realizando sus miedos sus inquietudes y sus pasiones todo y tienen la oportunidad de estar enfrente a ella y contemplarla Aprov chenlo Ma ana subo un video cont ndoles un poco m s sobre c mo encarar un Museo Las fotos son de obras en el metmuseum y en el themuseumofmodernart que saqu en mi ltimo viaje a Nueva York art beauty newyork metropolitanmuseumofart buenosaires travel modernart

text: Two Tahitian Women is an painting by Paul Gauguin It depicts two topless women one holding mango blossoms on the Pacific Island of Tahiti The painting is part of the permanent collection of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City Tahiti is depicted as an innocent paradise the two women in the painting confront the viewer in a way similar to that in Manet and follow an artistic tradition of comparing woman s breasts to flowers or fruit gauguin paulgaugin tahiti metropolitanmuseumofart met art masterpiece paintings toples mango mangoflower mangoflowers paradise flower fruts arte metropolitanmuseumofart metropolitan

text: Greek Pair of Gold Earrings with Dolphins Heads x x in nd st c BC coll Metropolitan Museum of Art NY I am accustomed to seeing Greek earrings of this general form but perhaps most often with lions heads and generally just of gold These dolphins heads seem unusual to me as does the use of emeralds and glass separated by bands of granulation Please realize that I speak out of almost total ignorance all this may be much less rare than I think I do know that they are extremely striking and decorative I d love to wear them This is not the first time I ve posted ancient jewellery I covet greek hellenistic earrings classical dolphin granulation gold metropolitanmuseumofart
