text: This version of Augustus Saint Gaudens Diana is actually only half the size of the version which served as a weather vane for the Madison Square Garden tower until Being the tallest fixture in the New York skyline at the turn of the century Diana s nudity caused a sensation and scandal Numerous attempts by the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice to have the statue torn down or covered by a cloth which blew away in the wind almost immediately all ended in vain Diana remained visible all the way to New Jersey and was the first monument in history to be lit at night by electricity She was only removed when the tower was demolished Shrouded in urban myth and legend many believe New York It Girl and silent film actress Evelyn Nesbit to be the model for the original Diana Nesbit herself would be the obsession of a media frenzy in when her drug addicted and mentally unstable husband architect Harry Kendall Thaw shot socialite Stanford White in the rooftop theatre of Madison Square Garden Thaw sought retribution of White for having raped Evelyn when she was just years old Evelyn divorced Thaw in and died in at the age of art history sculpture metropolitanmuseumofart newyorkcity dianaofthetower augustussaintgaudens evelynnesbit murder silentfilm scandal socialhistory madisonsquaregarden urbanmyth legend

text: Just wanted to share something I ve learned recently from askvinhHave you ever faced a problem that you could not solve But when you stood back or looked at it from a different angle you were able to see it differently and was able to create a solution Perhaps you were able to get input from the right person and they were able to help you find the solution Why couldn t you solve the problem the first time It s because you have fallen victim to silo mentality looking at the problem through one perspective So what did you do to find the solution You looked at the problem through a different perspective or was able to get someone else s perspectiveMy friends Perspective is Power When you are faced with a problem or adversity sometimes all you have to do is look at it from a different perspective or find the right people and get their perspective and you might just find the solution perspective convention problemsolving collaboration nyc metropolitanmuseumofart art shareknowledge tourist paintings entrepreneurminds ifyournotgrowingyourdying

text: Marseille My Fav Snap The Met NYC Part of The Arts do spark your memories Mary Philippe to commemorate the th anniversary of the death of Leonardo da Vinci The Met presents the artist s painting Saint Jerome Praying in the Wilderness begun around on special loan from the Vatican Museum The exquisitely rendered work represents Jerome A D a major saint and theologian of the Church The scene is based on the story of his later life which he spent as a hermit in the desert The unfinished painting provides an extraordinary glimpse into Leonardo s creative process and the paint surface reveals the presence of da Vinci s fingerprints I hope I can get snaps of his fingerprints Mary it may bring back the of your lost memories leonardodavinci davinci metropolitanmuseumofart nyc myfav explore travel artphoto artphotography adventure museum wanderlust wander travelphotography exhibit vaticanmuseum louiscomforttiffany art artist artphotography artphoto saintj r mepraying saintjeromeprayinginthewilderness saint catholicchurch vaticanart stjerome

text: Samuel Fosso Self Portrait Gelatin silver print in x in The Metropolitan Museum of Art New York Also apart of the Studio Museum in Harlem s collection On our street there was a studio photographer who I began to spend time with I asked him to teach me photography I spent five months as an apprentice after which I wanted to have my own studio The problem was making prints without wasting too much paper because as my uncle said You don t do business for loss you do business for gain But I found out that the owner didn t want me to leave because he had stopped losing money when I started working in his studio After learning that my uncle told me to find a space for my own studio and he bought me an enlarger Samuel Fosso Credit Aperture SamuelFosso BlackandBlueChip

text: I came across this beauty of a book while working on the suggested reading list for Snapshots of Early Modern History and had to buy it immediately There are a lot of really great art history books for kids but most of them stay quite surface level What I particularly love about this book is the way it digs in deeper and introduces art criticism It spends several pages on each painting it examines and includes multiple close up shots to really bring out the details of the painting What Makes a Rembrandt a Rembrandt is part of a series from the Metropolitan Museum of Art that also includes books on da Vinci Raphael Monet Degas Van Gogh and Picasso

name: 2019-08-30 20.01.49 2121838736061726053_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Take a closer look at the magnificent gilt gesso decoration on an extraordinary George I gilt gesso card table designed in the manner of James Moore Gilt gesso card tables are incredibly rare and only four known examples are known to survive today One of the tables is in the collection of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York the table is said to have come from the collections of the Earls of Carnarvon at Highclere Castle Berkshire The table was one of the few gilded pieces acquired by the esteemed English furniture collector Irwin Untermyer before he bequest his collection to the museum The pair to this table is in a private collection in the UK A fourth example was previously in the collection of Winston Guest and sold at Sotheby s in masterpiece antiques metropolitanmuseumofart highclerecastle artcollector antiques thcentury jamesmoore royalcollection gilding flowers sothebys houseandgarden howtospendit theworldofinteriors happyfriday decorativearts nationaltrust englishheritage museums

text: Happy birthday to Jacques Louis David born on this day in This sheet is an early exploration of the subject that Jacques Louis David would later treat in his painting The Death of Socrates which entered the Met s collection in The composition features the ancient Greek philosopher Socrates in his prison cell surrounded by disciples Sentenced to death by the Athenian courts for his unorthodox beliefs he prepares to drink from a cup of hemlock His gesture heavenward indicates that he has paused to expound upon his theory of the immortality of the human soul Jacques Louis David French The Death of Socrates ca pen and black ink with brush and gray wash over black chalk with light squaring in black chalk metonpaper metonpaper metdrawingsandprints metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart themet jacqueslouisdavid socrates deathofsocrates penandink drawing

text: Merced River Yosemite Valley by Albert Bierstadt Albert Bierstadt my favourite landscape painter was born in Germany in His family moved to the US when he was one year old When he was he began to paint in oils and two years later he moved back to Germany to study and paint Alpine landscapes When he was he returned to the US and travelled through the American West taking photographs and making sketches of the mountain ranges which he later painted in his New York studio His paintings were sold at record prices making him extremely successful financially but later decreased in popularity in the wake of impressionism When he was he moved to the Bahamas where he painted the tropics but continued to travel to the West and Canada to paint his beloved Rocky Mountains He died when he was having completed possibly around paintings

text: Jungulf Mott Viking Age sword variant original Pen ink charcoal and pencil on paper SwordSteel copper silver nielloWeight lbs oz g European probably Scandinavian th century The richly decorated hilt and pattern welded blade indicate that this sword was carried by a warrior of high rank perhaps a Viking chieftain or Frankish nobleman The braided copper wires on the pommel may represent an earlier Scandinavian custom of tying a protective talisman to a sword hilt The pattern welded blade was forged of intertwined rods of steel and iron a technique that produced a tough yet resilient blade with a distinctive swirling pattern on its surface Such blades were treasured for both their practical and decorative qualities Met accession number The Metropolitan Museum of Art New York City United States metmuseum jungulfmott jmott art artist illustration illustrator minneapolis mpls newyork newyorkcity nyc empirestate manhattan uppereastside themet metropolitanmuseumofart art archaeology artefactillustration artifactillustration technicaldrawing vikingsword carolingiansword artmuseum viking vikings vikingage frankish francia carolingian

text: Egyptian Fayum Entrance Area Necklace of Sithathoryunet with the Name of Senwosret Il Middle Kingdom Dynasty c BC coll of Metropolitan Museum of Art NY The pectoral x in is composed of gold carnelian lapis lazuli turquoise and garnet and the necklace in long of gold carnelian lapis lazuli turquoise and green feldspar Swipe for photo of back which is as finely finished as the front The cloisonn pectoral is inlaid with pieces of semi precious stones This is not just bling though it is utterly gorgeous adornment It is laden with symbolism far too complicated for me to list here do go to the Met s website for a full accounting Just as an example let me quote zigzag lines on the base bar represent the primordial waters out of which the primeval hill emerged Works like this inspired Art Deco jewellery of the s some of the most stunning examples are by Cartier and the fashion was fueled by the discovery of King Tutankhamun s tomb egyptian jewellery sithathoryunet middlekingdom dynasty artdeco cartier metropolitanmuseumofart tutankhamun

text: We can make an effort to be inspired or sometimes inspiration weaves itself into our lives in either active or passive ways but is still a breath of fresh air We are all inspired by the great master paintings I had the privilege to see Study of a Young Woman by Johannes Vermeer at the MET a few weeks ago However what we don t see is the collection of paintings that went in to make the masterpiece we see That collection may not have been worth showing but that is not to say that it did not in any way or form contribute towards the making of the piece The ingredients to the inspiration may be just as vital as the painting itself

text: Last month August I posted about The Holburne Museum s show douard Vuillard The Poetry of the Everyday Another prominent member of the group of Parisian painters known as Les Nabis was F lix Vallotton subject of an exhibition at the Royal Academy London F lix Vallotton Painter of Disquiet It continues to September at the RA and will be at the Met New York from October to January Many of the pictures were familiar from s F lix Vallotton Le Feu sous la glace The Fire under the Ice at the Grand Palais in Paris although that show probably benefited from fewer of Vallotton s nudes and more of his landscapes next post His ability as a painter is clear from still lifes like Le service caf The Coffee Service Poivrons rouges Red Peppers and his portraits Gertrude Stein Les Cinq Peintres The Five Painters the Nabis Vuillard nd from the left Vallotton on the right His woodcuts of contemporary Paris are in the tradition of Daumier Le Bon March La Manifestation The Demonstration and La Charge both also and showing that some things change little felixvallotton felixvallotonpainterofdisquiet royalacademyofarts royalacademy nabi lesnabis metropolitanmuseumofart

text: David Roentgen Rolltop Desk c x x in coll Metropolitan Museum of Art NY Like several of France s leading cabinet makers Roentgen was German he met great favor in ancien regime France and was appointed ebeniste mechanicien by Marie Antoinette The first owner of this extraordinary desk is not known but was presumably French it was in French collections until the end of the th century This tour de force is composed of many kinds of wood among them maple burl woods and mahogany mother of pearl gilded and tooled leather bronze steel and brass swipe to see one of the marquetry panels Roentgen was obviously proud of this creation for his initials appear loud and clear right above the kneehole drawer Roentgen was known for his mechanical ingenuity and this desk is a wonderful example it has all kinds of moving parts and secret drawers The Met has cleverly posted a video swipe next to it showing how it all works irresistible davidroentgen cabinetmaker ebeniste ancienr gime france marieantoinette metropolitanmuseumofart rolltopdesk

text: Walking into the Metropolitan Museum of Art s CAMP exhibit had my head going round and round in circles because these extravagant artistic larger than life displays of exuberant fashion make me so loopy On the left the purple feathered circular blob form with a multicolored swarm of butterflies zooming round and round is intoxicating romantic for I hope to meet someone who makes my heart skip a beat like this one day Check out how skinny her legs are On the right a lilac expertly pleated and tiered strapless bow gown with some moss green shirring at the bodice is styled on the mannequin form backwards Fashion is so interesting and stumps you in imaginable ways I definitely find myself taking a step back on more than a few occasions and wondering what the artist was thinking at that moment in time when the dress silhouette was altered and flipped to the mannequin s feet Wild creation Next picture metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart museum ilovemuseums ilovemuseum iloveart ilovefashion ilovefashion fashionandart fashionworld artworld butterflies butterflies butterfliesofinstagram butterflies lovers mannequinfashion extremefashion fashionshop fashionartist pleateddress tiereddress fashionbackwards fashioninterestgram fashiongram abstractfashion fashionmuseum fashionexhibition fashionexhibit fashionexhibitions fashionhoarder fashionable

text: last year I had the chance to visit the metropolitanmuseumofart in newyork I literally spent the whole trip literally tripping and visiting art galleries I was so amused by this specific museum though because of its brilliant collection obviously but it was really so informational and brushed on every ancient era capturing the culture and essence of what our ancestors believed in and lived like I spent hours at this museum and I didn t even get to see it all But Davincis art work happened to be on display that day so that was wicked to experience Couldn t even believe I was surrounded by so many important artifacts that tell the stories and show the soul of many tribes and dynasties before us The work of the Greats you could literally feel it This power inspired me SOo I decided I m going to do something with all of these pictures that I captured because they deserve to be brought back to life exalted and honored When I m done with all of these I ll post them on my flickr and website for you all to see Till then stay safe my friends and remember to stay true to your roots metmuseum galactica collageart digital magic artifacts ancientcivilization ancientarchitecture breatheart makeartinstead newyork practicemakesperfect

text: Castellani Firm of Necklace with Cameo of Veronica s Veil c gold and sapphires length of chain with tassels in cameo x in coll of Metropolitan Museum of Art NY The firm of Castellani was founded in Rome in and closed in It was immensely successful pioneering the production of archaeological jewellery This opulent necklace features a seriously religious image carved on a luscious sapphire which to me somewhat secularizes it if that is a word As Christ was walking up the Via Dolorosa to His crucifixion St Veronica cleansed His face of blood and sweat with her veil that image was imprinted on the veil The Castellani collection of ancient jewellery and the firm s own work is housed at the Villa Giulia in Rome Years ago it was rather a secret and one had to ask and to surrender one s passport before being admitted now it is on open view and pretty stunning it is castellani archaeologicaljewellery rome villagiulia stveronica veil metropolitanmuseumofart

text: Andy Warhol Pink and purple cow According to Warhol the inspiration for the cow image came from art dealer Ivan Karp Another time he said Why don t you paint some cows they re so wonderfully pastoral and such a durable image in the history of the arts Ivan talked like this I don t know how pastoral he expected me to make them but when he saw the huge cow heads bright pink on a bright yellow background that I was going to have made into rolls of wallpaper he was shocked But after a moment he exploded with They re super pastoral They re ridiculous They re blazingly bright and vulgar I mean he loved those cows and for my next show we papered all the walls in the gallery with them andywarhol andywarholmuseum popart fashion urbanfashion streetfashion luxurystreetwear instafashion fashionposts artsy painting paintings uniqueclothing fashiondesigner fashiondesign fashionart fashionstyle louvre art museum classicalart museum modernartmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart louvre louvremuseum museums museumofmodernart

text: Claude Monet Waterloo bridge Sunlight Effect If not for the fog Claude Monet once remarked London wouldn t be a beautiful city It s the fog that gives it its magnificent breadth While working on his London series he rose early every day to paint Waterloo Bridge in the morning moving on to Charing Cross Bridge at midday and in the afternoon He observed both motifs from his fifth floor window at the Savoy Hotel The Art Institute s two Waterloo Bridge paintings are dated and but both were likely begun in and dated only when Monet felt that they were finished He worked on all of his London paintings in his studio in Giverny refusing to send any of them to his dealer until he was satisfied with them as an ensemble claudemonet claudemonetgardens impressionism fashion urbanfashion streetfashion luxurystreetwear instafashion fashionposts artsy painting paintings uniqueclothing fashiondesigner fashiondesign fashionart fashionstyle louvre art museum classicalart museum modernartmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart louvre louvremuseum museums museumofmodernart

name: 2019-09-03 08.30.32 2124389896396574584_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: UK punk subculture began in the early s and quickly spread into American pop culture It embodied a style an ideology and a way of life for those who rejected capitalism authoritarianism and emphasized a do it yourself attitude Self made clothing often held together in rudimentary ways and paired with Dr Martens boots became the standard look for punks Punk made a mainstream revival in the s as the grunge movement rebirthed these anti establishment ideals High end fashion houses began to adopt the cheap hand made aesthetic of punk clothing but with quality craftsmanship and materials In the MET s exhibit PUNK Chaos to Couture this transition is epitomized by two of Versace s S S gowns The black of the pair is by far the more infamous Made of silk and lycra and held together by large good safety pins the dress was worn by Elizabeth Hurley when she accompanied Hugh Grant to the premier of Four Weddings and a Funeral Her appearance in the dress made international headlines though many criticized her revealing choice Hurley states that the dress was a last minute decision as it was the only option available from the Versace office The dress was also worn by Lady Gaga in who showcased many archived Versace pieces that year fashion versace punk punkmovement punkfashion met metropolitanmuseumofart couture elizabethhurley hughgrant ladygaga

text: Now I have some downtime with Hurricane Dorian on our site l ll continue sharing with you work of art metmuseum This huge work by Thomas Hart Benton Offering a panorama of American life throughout the s America Today is a room sized mural comprising ten canvas panels Missouri native Thomas Hart Benton painted America Today to adorn a boardroom on the third floor of the New School for Social Research a center of progressive thought and education in Greenwich Village The mural was commissioned in by the New School s director Alvin Johnson Benton finished it very early in when the school opened a new building designed by architect Joseph Urban Although the artist received no fee for his work on commission he was paid with free eggs the yolks from which he created the egg tempera paint thomashartbentonart metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart nyc enjoyart beart

text: Almond Blossom was painted immediately before one of his attacks My work was going well he informed his brother the last canvas of branches in blossom you will see that it is perhaps the best the most patiently worked thing I had done painted with calm and with greater firmness of touch And the next day down like a brute Poised between lucidity and desperation this lacework of light and color is kept aloft by the confidence Van Gogh had acquired in the previous two or three years and the sheer technical finesse now at his command In painting the Almond Blossom Van Gogh was not out to revive his own optimism but to make an offering to his ever caring brother In spring Theo had married Jo Bonger and in February she gave birth to their son whom they named Vincent after the boy s godfather The Blossoming Almond Tree was van Gogh s present to the infant that would perpetuate his name vincentvangogh vincentvangoghmuseum almondblossom impressionism fashion urbanfashion streetfashion luxurystreetwear instafashion fashionposts artsy painting paintings uniqueclothing fashiondesigner fashiondesign fashionart fashionstyle louvre art museum classicalart museum modernartmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart louvre louvremuseum museums museumofmodernart

text: The Antioch Chalice consists of a small cup encased in a decorated gilded shell It was discovered in the early th century in Syria but is believed to be originally from Antioch This city is one of the five early pillars of the Christian church the others being Rome Jerusalem Constantinople and Alexandria The outer shell is decorated with plant life animals and twelve figures Two of the figures represent Christ while the other ten are philosophers and prophets who foretold His coming After its discovery the Antioch Chalice was identified as the Holy Grail or the cup that Jesus used at the Last Supper It was believed that the interior piece was the Grail itself while the decoration had been added later in order to honor it It was displayed all over America as the Holy Grail and people came in droves to see it However further testing revealed that it is most likely an oil lamp from the th century The Antioch Chalice can now be seen at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City

text: Smartphones wave like palm fronds above the viewers who throng Leonardo da Vinci s St Jerome at the Met through October a shrine like display of a painting that the Master started around and then abandoned perhaps when its commission lapsed but as likely owing to ennui Leonardo had fully drawn only the face clavicle area and right foot of the old nearly toothless Jerome who is about to pound himself in the chest with a rock as he contemplates a crucifix in a cave or a grotto A glum brown undercoat occupies much of the wood panel The saint s sketched companion animal a lion appears to roar at him for some reason The work s torqued composition and canny human anatomy are impressive but it registers mainly as a relic for the contemporary cult of Leonardo the innovator s innovator which dates from Bill Gate s purchase in of one of his notebooks How exciting is it that a Leonardo fingerprint appears in the paint Your call bethsorenson thenewyorker museum leonardodavinci stjerome met metropolitanmuseumofart october painting master leonardo face foot toothless jerome crucifix sketched lion humananatomy impressive contemporary cult innovator billgates notebooks fingerprint paint nyc manhattan

text: Vincent van Gogh The Alpilles with Olive Trees in the Foreground Of Olive Trees in a Mountainous Landscape in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art MoMA Vincent wrote his brother Theo I did a landscape with olive trees and also a new study of a starry sky calling this painting the daylight complement to the nocturnal The Starry Night His intention was to go beyond the photographic and silly perfection of some painters to an intensity born of color and linear rhythms Within the painting twisted green olive trees stand before the foothills of the Alps and underneath the sky with an ectoplasmic cloud Later when the pictures had dried he sent both of them to Theo in Paris noting The olive trees with the white cloud and the mountains behind as well as the rise of the moon and the night effect are exaggerations from the point of view of the general arrangement the outlines are accentuated as in some old woodcuts vincentvangogh vincentvangoghmuseum almondblossom impressionism fashion urbanfashion streetfashion luxurystreetwear instafashion fashionposts artsy painting paintings uniqueclothing fashiondesigner fashiondesign fashionart fashionstyle louvre art museum classicalart museum modernartmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart louvre louvremuseum museums museumofmodernart

name: 2019-09-05 01.04.33 2125614975444442611_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: One of only a few extant examples of an Early Netherlandish painting executed in distemper on canvas this picture was completed by Justus of Ghent around The colors which would have once been vibrant have deteriorated quite heavily due to the fragility of the medium Justus of Ghent also known as Joos Van Wassenhove began his career in Ghent it is thought that he may have worked in the studio of Dieric Bouts and he was friendly with Hugo van der Goes but left for Italy in to work for Federigo da Montefeltro the Duke of Urbino This canvas depicts the Adoration of the Magi however the figures are shown inside a decaying formal building instead of the stable in which they are normally pictured The Virgin sits upon a canopied bed and the glass of wine and bread on the table symbolize the Holy Eucharist

name: 2019-09-05 01.06.16 2125615845745107599_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Claude Monet Water lilies One instant one aspect of nature contains it all said Claude Monet referring to his late masterpieces the water landscapes that he produced at his home in Giverny between and his death in These works replaced the varied contemporary subjects he had painted from the s through the s with a single timeless motif water lilies The focal point of these paintings was the artist s beloved ower garden which featured a water garden and a smaller pond spanned by a Japanese Footbridge Over time the artist became less and less concerned with conventional pictorial space By the time he painted Water Lilies which comes from his third group of these works he had dispensed with the horizon line altogether In this spatially ambiguous canvas the artist looked down focusing solely on the surface of the pond with its cluster of vegetation oating amid the re ection of sky and trees claudemonet claudemonetgardens impressionism fashion urbanfashion streetfashion luxurystreetwear instafashion fashionposts artsy painting paintings uniqueclothing fashiondesigner fashiondesign fashionart fashionstyle louvre art museum classicalart museum modernartmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart louvre louvremuseum museums museumofmodernart

text: Robe l Anglaise ca British silk Credit Line Purchase Irene Lewisohn Bequest Accession Number a bThis robe l anglaise is a superb expression of the English taste in dress skillful cut and construction and free from elaborate trimmings a sensibility that increasingly influenced European modes of dress in the late eighteenth century The refined simplicity and neat tailoring associated with English dress grew increasingly influential in France during the latter half of the eighteenth century By the s French fashion magazines regularly featured the robe l anglaise praising its elegance and modest charm This example is impeccably made and discreetly adorned its sole ornamentation being bands of pinked self fabric trim The choice of textile a delicately patterned silk damask dating to the s is evidence of the common eighteenth century practice of repurposing finely woven fabrics https www metmuseum org art collection search metmuseum metmuseumnyc metropolitanmuseumofart metropolitanmuseum museum newyork ny allabout thcentury robealanglaise anglaise reddress damask reddamask thcenturyfashion thcentury instagram fashion fashionstudy metmuseum

text: CAMP a few of my favs from the CAMP exhibit the Metropolitan Museum of Art NYC it was an AMAZING style exhibit that blew my mind gave me so much insight into what one can do w fashion The exhibit examines how the elements of irony humor parody theatricality and exaggeration r expressed in fashion I hav to admit some the styles I was attracted too were somewhat modest considering the overall presentation I wish now I had taken photos of the more exaggerated styles but here a man s suit frm the th century has inspired me to thrift a similar jacket style w leggins jeans so i ll definitely b heading more over to the men s section when i thrift LiveLoveStyle campexhibit metropolitanmuseumofart nycstylin seveenthcenturytothepresent notesoncamp susansontag fashion style mystyle styleover styleover ardisbougiethriftstyle

name: 2019-09-05 21.22.15 2126227863619720123_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: This abstract by my favourite world renowned master of colour Petro Lebedynets is my choice of art for my study above the desk Difficult to summarise in a few sentences why I love his works so much I could write endless essays One of the most important reasons would be to me is his profound attention to colour Colour is stronger than the language It s a subliminal communication Louise Bourgeois There were artists who were very specific about the space the placement and positioning of their art Gunter Forg Soulages etc In line with this I like installing Petro Lebedynets s works in storied contexts as I did in my study beautiful antique English desk and an antique rug from Russian Imperial Family Romanovs The legend goes that the Russian Emperor Nicolas the Second used to walk on it I hope my to do list will be done quicker in this study Swipe to see more Upholstery by Dedar Rubelli Armanicasa pierresoulages

text: Theodore Robinson The Old Mill oil on canvas The first American artist to be given the predicate of Impressionist in the USA When he finally returned to the USA permanently at the end of he remained faithful to landscape painting successfully But measured against Monet his views are dependent on a more subdued coloration and place greater emphasis on the aspect of linear structuring coordinates Altogether the reception of Impressionism by American artists is generally characterised by the fact that the French stylistic form represented only one of several parallel Europeans models Academic and realistic composition and coloration often provided them with stimuli of equal status from Impressionism Reimagining Art by Norbert Wolf theodorerobinson impressionism oiloncanvas oilpainting peinture pintura painting impressionist art arte artlovers landscapepainting oldmill artbook coffeetablebook americanart americana metropolitanmuseumofart

text: Unto This Last Two Hundred Years of John Ruskin is open now through December The Victorian polymath visionary uncompromising contradictory and sometimes troubling remains one of the greatest writers on art in the English language His ideas demand our attention today as we address the progression of issues he observed in his time As such we focus on Ruskin as a pioneering ecologist advocate for social justice and historic preservationist The timing could not be better to take another look at what he called the coming storm Featuring Yale s combined collections of Ruskiniana the largest outside the UK with exceptional loans from metmuseum fitzmuseum uk beineckelibrary themorganlibrary among others Image credits left to right JohnRuskin In the Pass of Killiecrankie watercolor and gouache on board The Fitzwilliam Museum University of Cambridge Frederick Hollyer Portrait of John Ruskin Datur Hora Quieti ca platinum print Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library YaleUniversity John Ruskin Study of an OakLeaf undated pen and brown ink with watercolor over graphite heightened with gouache and gum onpaper Yale Center for British Art Paul Mellon Collection John Ruskin The Dryad s Waywardness from Modern Painters London Smith Elder and Co vol plate Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library Yale University J M W Turner Venice from the Porch of Madonna della Salute ca oil on canvas The MetropolitanMuseumofArt New York Bequest of Cornelius Vanderbilt

text: These first two images are front and back details of a tapestry panel woven at the Royal Gobelins Manufactory in Paris in the th century as part of a larger commission for the sixth Earl of Coventry and his house Croome Court in England When an object is too large to fit on tables we have the option of using a hoist system to hang large textiles for staff examinations or photography see image The central panel where you see the white fabric is undecorated because it is meant to be covered by a mirror This piece was added later with painted borders by Conservator Nancy Britton in metobjectsconservation to blend seamlessly with the woven th century side panels see image Mirror surround with vases designed woven General conception by Jacques Germain Soufflot Manufacture National des Gobelins Paris Gobelins Tapestry RattiTextileCenter MetTextiles MetMuseum MetropolitanMuseumofArt

text: With approximately exhibitions Jane Peterson had a highly successful career While her style varied from Impressionist to Expressionist her use of color and the spontaneity of her execution both encouraged by her teacher Joaquin Sorolla remained constant Through Sorolla Peterson met and befriended Louis Comfort Tiffany with whom she traveled on painting expeditions and whose garden at Laurelton Hall she painted many times an example can be seen at the Metropolitan Museum of Art Turkish Fountain with Garden While the subject matter of Peterson s work varied she often used floral arrangements which she called flower portraits as a means of studying color as she likely did here Although Peterson focused mostly on floral portraits during her brief year marriage at years old she painted countless numbers of cityscapes during her lifetime depicting the beauty of the many foreign cities she called home throughout her life Out of the vaults Jane Peterson s Petunias and Zinnias ca Now on view in American Still Life Moderns janepeterson womenartists expressionistart joaquinsorolla louiscomforttiffany themet metropolitanmuseumofart floralpainting stilllife feministarthistory womenknowhistory arthistory

name: 2019-09-06 21.08.40 2126945810654838454_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Francisco Toledo July Sept Expressionist painter Francisco Toledo who was well known and respected in Mexico both for his art and his activism has died the country s president announced late Thursday President Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador wrote in his Twitter account that art is mourning He called the year old Toledo an authentic defender of nature customs and traditions of our people Toledo s enigmatic paintings and sculptures were marked by the animals colors and traditions of Oaxaca Insects cats and other animals were presented in almost mythological contexts in Toledo s work whose colors also evoked the brilliant palette of Oaxaca Wild haired and bearded Toledo led movements to save old convents and other colonial era buildings from developers and helped turn them into centers for the arts and gardens Culture Secretary Alejandra Frausto wrote of the artist something flowered at every step Toledo took He also founded the Museum de Arte Contemporane de Oaxaca MACO the Patronato Pro Defensa y Conservaci n del Patrimonio Cultural de Oaxaca a library for the blind a photographic center and the Eduardo Mata Music Library Francisco Toledo has had exhibitions in Argentina Brazil Colombia Ecuador Spain the United Kingdom Belgium France Japan Sweden the United States as well as other countries His work is represented in the permanent collections of the Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Museum of Modern Art in New York and the Museo Tamayo in Mexico City Mono con Bicicleta The Wanderer Toledo FranciscoToledo Expressionist Painter Mexico activism PresidentAndresManuelLopezObrador Twitter artismourning nature tradition AlejandreFrausto MuseumdeArteContemporanedeOaxaca Argentina Brazil Colombia Ecuador Spain UK Belgium France Japan Sweden UnitedStates MetropolitanMuseumofArt MuseumofModernArt NewYork MuseoTamayo MexicoCity

text: The Metropolitan Museum of Art New York One of the most inspirational places for art and fashion hosted an exhibition called CAMP It explores the origins of Camp s exuberant aesthetic and how the sensibility evolved from a place of marginality to become an important influence on mainstream culture In these images we can see ANDY WARHOL S iconic Campbell Soups Cans Dress which is world famous BALENCIAGA HOUSE OF MOSCHINO VIVIENNE WESTWOOD MARY KATRANTZOU and several other designers evolving in their fashion journey and inculcating architectural structures into their designs DelnaPoonawallaDesigns InspirationalNYC NYC NewYork NewYorkCity NYCInspired MET MetropolitanMuseumOfArt Camp CampExhibition FashionInspo AndyWarhol Balenciaga HouseOfMoschino VivienneWestwood MaryKatrantzou InternationalDesigners DelnaPoonawalla HolidayDiaries HolidayInspiration DesignInspo Designer

text: th Muharram th September Lullaby UV print on polyester film back lit by LED panel x inches Crib of the Infant Jesus Wood polychromy lead silver gilt painted parchment silk embroidery with seed pearls gold thread and translucent enamels x x cm th century Wish I had a whole other lifetime to study religious symbols and their migrations from continent to continent their astounding fluidity Image is a digital collage that I made for the stationsofthecross along with an animated short exploring commonalities between Shia and Christian iconographies and mourning remembrance rites It is made up of photographs that I took at an imambargah in Lahore The cradle represents Husayn ibn Ali s infant son and his martyrdom in Karbala Image shows another cradle housed at the Met New York symbolising the Christ Child Both are examples of devotional objects particularly central to female led religious observances ashura mourningtraditions husaynibnali karbala islamicart christianart iconography rites southasianart artfrompakistan devotionalart themet metropolitanmuseumofart

text: The lighter the skin the more acceptable you are The darker the skin the more marginalised you become I want to demonstrate that you can produce beauty in the context of a figure that has that kind of velvety blackness It can be done Kerry James Marshall b Untitled Studio Acrylic on PVC panels Black skin is a constant in Mr Marshall s art More than three decades ago he resolved to devote himself to creating a new disruptive art history one that would insert big time the absent black figure into the tradition of Western art which was a tradition he loved and identified with Working across various media in portraits interiors nudes and landscapes Marshall combines actual and imagined events from African American history and culture and integrates a range of stylistic influences to address the limited historiography of black art blackisbeautiful odetomanet olympia beauty manet color artismylife modernart americanhistory kerryjamesmarshall metropolitanmuseumofart negativespace artiststudio artinspired arthistory

text: Kicked off Fashion Week more like Fashion Week weekend for me in NYC with the amazing joyadass at The Metropolitan Museum of Art Joya a CNN anchor and founder of Lady Drinks a networking platform primarily for South Asian professional women hosted a private tour of the Met s Fashion Through the Ages Thrilled to personally experience one of Joya s events and meet some of her members scroll Joya and I have spent a lot of time supporting one another through our own women s network so seeing her in action was well a joy Love the comfy sneakers Joya I m bringing mine next time And the icing on the evening was having dear friend lauriehardenstylist from San Francisco be able to join us scroll again We also have spent hours talking biz and years supporting one another both personally and professionally Our families go way back Laurie is one of those people who lights up a room with her beauty and kindness So glad you were able to make it girl Loved that vintage duster too Great to be in the company of such fine women supporting each other Here s to the entrepreneurial sisterhood dressingwellboston nyfashionweek metropolitanmuseumofart ladydrinksnyc lauriehardenstylist womensupportingwomen entrepreneurialsisterhood kickingofffallinstyle

text: Robe la Fran aise French Standard European silhouettes of the eighteenth century accommodated a world of change and specifically a changing world dominated by new textile techniques from Asia and the Middle East This French textile emulates ikat a technique in which yarns are tie dyed before weaving in a manner then known as a result of a geographic mistake as chin The softened edges of the ikat do not mitigate a bold textile design nor do they entirely surrender to the authority of the Western shaping Pinked edge pleated and ruched self fabric see detail trace the form of the open robe An eighteenth century template of dress is all but unchanging yet the influence of new material requires a syncretism In terms of eighteenth century revivals it is important to recognize how much the classic forms of eighteenth century dress accommodated translations into arresting new textile forms in the s and even the new textiles in the cottons of the s Date Culture FrenchMedium silkCredit Line Purchase Irene Lewisohn Bequest Accession Number C I a bhttps www metmuseum org art collection search robealafrancaise francaise museum fashionmuseum metmuseum metmuseumnyc metropolitanmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart nyc hautecouture chanel dior allabout thcentury tagdesoffenendenkmals thcentury warpprint thcenturyfashion metmuseum

text: Frankenstrat Graphite sketch Eddie Van Halen playing his custom built Frankenstrat guitar circa A hybrid of a Fender and a Gibson the Frankenstrat with its distinctive striped paint job was used by Van Halen throughout the s and s It was originally black and white on the cover of Van Halen s debut album and was later repainted the red black and white color scheme for which it is most recognizable Retired in the s the original Frankenstrat guitar is currently on display at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City playitloud metropolitanmuseumofart themet nyc edwardvanhalen eddievanhalen vanhalen frankenstrat gibsonguitars fenderguitars guitargods rockstars rockguitar

name: 2019-09-09 06.58.36 2128692279951703712_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Treasure Wall painting from Room H of the Villa of P Fannius Synistor at Boscoreale BC Civilization Ancient Rome Where NewYork Metropolitan MuseumPhoto metmuseum Family europe treasures contemporary treasures tesori italiani This fresco painting x cm of a seated woman playing a kithara is from Room H either a dining room triclinium or a room for social gatherings oecus in the villa at Boscoreale Each of the paintings that originally adorned this room derives from the Greek tradition of megalographia or large scale painting about which so much was written in antiquity Apollinaris of Sidonius Petronius in the Satyricon and Vitruvius all shed light on the use of megalographia in Roman villas In this fresco the kithara player is depicted as a plump young woman clothed in a purple chiton and white himation She is adorned with a bracelet earrings and headband with a central medallion all of gold A small figure of Atlas supports the arm of her elaborately carved chair that originally was lacquered a deep lustrous red The instrument she plays is not a simple lyre but a gilded kithara a large concert instrument played by Apollo and professional musicians Behind the seated woman stands a small girl wearing a sleeveless purple chiton She too is adorned with a gold headband bracelet and loop earrings Like portrait figures the woman and the girl gaze directly at the spectator Most recently it has been suggested that the pair may represent a Macedonian queen or princess and her daughter or younger sister The gilded kithara and richly adorned thronelike chair as well as the carefully rendered gold jewelry and headbands give the impression of royal personage Whatever the exact subject this painting and others in the villa were admired as excellent copies of Hellenistic art that emphasized the erudition and worldliness of the villa s owner italy italia archaeology archeologia arqueologia arqueolog a roman roma imperio romanhistory history text: Play It Loud The Instruments of Rock Roll is an exhibit at metropolitanmuseum highlighting instruments that not only created iconic recordings and performances but serve as some of the most important cultural touchstones in recent history They certainly feel that way to me I can t begin to say how in awe I was to be so close to these works of art that touched my life so powerfully Shown here are in order of the pictures are instruments from the Beatles Prince Eric Clapton Led Zeppelin Stevie Ray Vaughan Joan Jett with a hint of Steve Miller KISS with a glimpse of Ronnie Wood and Heart The Eagles and Prince again So many to see that it needs one more post to show Coming soon The exhibit runs through Oct It is more than worth checking out adventuresindogsandrealestate petfriendlyrealtor petfriendly realestateagent realtorlife nycphotographer nycphotography playitloud photoview metropolitanmuseumofart newyork nyc themet thebeatles prince ericclapton ledzeppelin cityphotography stevierayvaughan igphoto joanjett kiss photography theeagles ig nyc photographer realtorlife midtownmanhattan midtown museum

text: W conciergeq URHere metmuseum Isn t this such a powerful sculpture I m absolutely in love The Facade Commission Wangechi Mutu The NewOnes will free UsKenyan American artist Wangechi Mutu has been selected to create sculptures for The Met s Fifth Avenue facade niches the first ever such installation on the Museum s historic exterior inaugurating a new annual artist commission series Born in Nairobi in and trained in sculpture at Yale from which she received her MFA in Wangechi Mutu is one of the most distinguished artists of her generation She has achieved critical acclaim for her haunting otherworldly collage paintings art films live performances and sculptures Comprised of either bronze or organic materials Mutu s three dimensional work depicts formidable figures referencing modern and classical mythologies that conflate histories and sculptural traditions of Africa and Europe Like her collage paintings Mutu s sculptures reflect critically on social and ecological injustices and inequalities Female transformation and empowerment are at the core of all her ideas and evidence in the completed work Where The Met Fifth Avenue Facadelocated outside at nd Street and Fifth AvenuePhotographed by charlie portraits metmuseum wangechimutu art bronze sculpture museum ny nyny nyc newyorkcity fineart artist sculptor beautiful woman african metropolitanmuseumofart newyork love gorgeous breathtaking elegant

text: year old pic this is I tried to wear this dress today after around years and it decided to NOT fit into me I had mixed feelings I was happy I gained a few kilos but sad as I will have to give away one of my fav dresses I have had my share of body shamming experiences You are so thin are you not well Do you eat properly You have grown thinner Blah blah Even though I have always been a self confident person when I was younger it used to affect me Especially during my teenage and early twenties I blamed it on my premature birth I am month born I gave excuses Now as I am growing older I laugh at those comments Pity their ignorance My focus is on leading a healthy life Though I try to gain a few kilos I concentrate more on my health than my physical shapes and size It comes as a surprise to many that I am a hardcore foodie and my diet is absolutely normal In fact I eat anything and everything and off course way more than you think So be careful when you invite me to your home next My humble request Kindly don t say Why are you fat or why are you thin Especially when you have no other good things to say I mean think about the question you might be asking in the most innocent tone but is this even a logical question randommusing randommusings againstbodyshamming bodyshamming metropolitanmuseumofart throwback nyc newyork photooftheday blogger writersofinsta ilovetowrite storyteller travelblogger aspiringwriter amazonkdp writersofinstagram

text: The Metropolitan Museum of Art New York One of the most inspirational places for art and fashion hosted an exhibition called CAMP It explores the origins of Camp s exuberant aesthetic and how the sensibility evolved from a place of marginality to become an important influence on mainstream culture In the exhibit there were legendary designers such as Andy Warhol Vivienne Westwood Mary Katrantzou Elsa Schiaparelli Yves Saint Laurent Paul Poiret House Of Moschino Balenciaga and several other designers evolving in their fashion journey and inculcating structures and colours into their designs DelnaPoonawallaDesigns InspirationalNYC NYC NewYork NewYorkCity NYCInspired MET MetropolitanMuseumOfArt Camp CampExhibition FashionInspo AndyWarhol Balenciaga HouseOfMoschino VivienneWestwood MaryKatrantzou InternationalDesigners DelnaPoonawalla HolidayDiaries HolidayInspiration DesignInspo Designer

text: tashadwhaj with conciergeq URHere metmuseum Isn t this such a powerful sculpture I m absolutely in love The Facade Commission Wangechi Mutu The NewOnes will free UsKenyan American artist Wangechi Mutu has been selected to create sculptures for The Met s Fifth Avenue facade niches the first ever such installation on the Museum s historic exterior inaugurating a new annual artist commission series Born in Nairobi in and trained in sculpture at Yale from which she received her MFA in Wangechi Mutu is one of the most distinguished artists of her generation She has achieved critical acclaim for her haunting otherworldly collage paintings art films live performances and sculptures Comprised of either bronze or organic materials Mutu s three dimensional work depicts formidable figures referencing modern and classical mythologies that conflate histories and sculptural traditions of Africa and Europe Like her collage paintings Mutu s sculptures reflect critically on social and ecological injustices and inequalities Female transformation and empowerment are at the core of all her ideas and evidence in the completed work Where The Met Fifth Avenue Facadelocated outside at nd Street and Fifth AvenuePhotographed by charlie portraits metmuseum wangechimutu art bronze sculpture museum ny nyny nyc newyorkcity fineart artist sculptor beautiful woman african metropolitanmuseumofart newyork love gorgeous breathtaking elegant travel travelgram travelblogger conciergeq

text: Jean Pierre de Bougainville Louis de Carmontelle FrenchBorn Louis Carrogis the son of a cobbler Carmontelle used his wit and talent to elevate his social position eventually becoming employed in the d Orl ans court where his duties included tutoring the duke s son designing gardens and staging plays As a draftsman he left a legacy of watercolor portraits representing a broad swath of enlightenment society The sitter the scholar Jean Pierre de Bougainville was named to the Acad mie des Inscriptions and then with the backing of Madame de Pompadour elected to the Acad mie Fran aise in De Bougainville would die at age forty a real loss for the world of letters according to a manuscript penned near the end of Carmontelle s life by his friend Richard de L dans Perrin Stein March Artist Louis de Carmontelle French Paris Paris Date Medium Watercolor over graphite and black and red chalkDimensions sheet x cmClassification DrawingsCredit Line Gift of Mrs Charles Wrightsman Accession Number louisdecarmontelle carmontelle rococo french paris metmuseum metropolitanmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart museum redsuit thcenturyinterior interior genrepainting thcentury menwithstyle instgay allabout thcentury instagay metmuseum

text: For the first time in years the MetropolitanMuseumofArt is filling the exterior niches lining its Fifth Avenue entrance The Museum tapped Kenyan born artist WangechiMutu to inaugurate its new artist facade series commission with four sculptures which will be on view this week through January th To adorn the entrance Mutu constructed four bronze statues of seated women all of whom are crowned blinded and gagged by highly polished discs Born of traditions both European and African these graceful commanding figures will change the face of the museum literally and figuratively the nytimes writes It is testament to Mutu s belief that like street theater or religious rituals art can nudge viewers toward congregation metmuseum

text: Marble Statue Group of the Three Graces nd century A D Roman copy of a Greek work of the nd century B C These young girls linked in a dance like pose represent The Three Graces Aglaia Beauty Euphrosyne Mirth and Thalia Abundance They bestow what is most pleasurable and beneficent in nature and society fertility and growth beauty in the arts harmonious reciprocity between men They enjoyed venerable cults in Greece and Asia Minor In mythology they play an attendant role gracing festivals and organizing dances Their closest connection is with Aphrodite whom they serve as handmaidens This carefully calculated frieze like composition is typical of classicizing art of the second and first centuries B C Instantly recognizable it soon became the canonic formula for representing the Graces who appeared in every medium and on every kind of object from mirrors to sarcophagi On view at The Met Fifth Avenue in Gallery metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart met gallery virtualartgallery groupofthethreegraces marble marblesculptures aglaia euphrosyne thalia metmuseum museumholic museum sculpture gallery

text: The advent of the microscope in the early seventeenth century revolutionized the manner in which people saw insects In about ants bees and butterflies garnered most scholarly attention owing to their significance in biblical and classical sources By the eighteenth century the range of insects that were subjects of study had expanded in tandem with a new interest in understanding insects anatomies The two smaller less familiar insects depicted in this drawing operate as a framing device for the large blue beetle at its center Come see this drawing along with a selection of insect imagery on view in The Met s Robert Wood Johnson Jr Gallery Gallery through November Anonymous Dutch th century Studies of a Blue Beetle and Insects Gouache and watercolor Bequest of Catherine G Curran naturestudy bug beetle coprophanaeusensifer thcentury gouache watercolor insect currentlyonview noneedtoguess metonpaper metonpaper metdrawingsandprints metropolitanmuseumofart metmuseum themet

text: According to her legend St Juliana of Nicomedia was cruelly tortured and eventually beheaded for refusing to marry a pagan lord She was widely venerated later in the Middle Ages not least in Perugia where a convent was dedicated to her honour In Abbess Gabriella of Santa Guiliana convinced the neighbouring monastery of San Domenico to hand over their relic of St Juliana s head thus acquiring for her convent a powerful relic of their patron saint Gabriella had this head reliquary commissioned from an artist working in the circle of celebrated sculptor Giovanni di Bartolo to house the relic and furthermore had an elaborate gilded tabernacle constructed to display it Some time after the Convent of Santa Guiliana was suppressed in this reliquary bust fell into private hands It was bought by the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York in legend hagiography saints saint catholicsaint stjuliana martyr martyrdom middleages moyenage mittelalter medioevo edadmedia perugia santaguiliana patronsaint head relic reliquary fourteenthcentury latemedieval metmuseum metropolitanmuseumofart nyc nycart medievalart medieval medievalsculpture medievalhistory medievalitaly

text: The shopfront from quai de Bourbon Ile Saint Louis Paris between with later replacements is displayed in the Wrightsman Galleries of the Metropolitan Museum of Art NYC as a gift from J Pierpont Morgan As seen in the Chester Price rendering from House Garden magazine it had been added to a seventeenth century building a rare survivor of retail architecture of the Louis XVI period By the time it was dismantled during World War I the paint had worn away to expose the bare oak so the natural finish was retained in the restoration for the museum in keeping with the tastes of the time metropolitanmuseumofart wrightsmangalleries chesterbprice architecturalrendering houseandgarden louisxvi periodroomsofthemet retailarchitecture shopfront jpmorgan

text: RichardMorrisHunt a leading architect of the GildedAge designed the facade of the MetropolitanMuseumofArt the pedestal of the StatueofLiberty and many other public and private projects For his Administration Building at the World s Columbian Exhibition in Chicago in Hunt received the Gold Medal of the Royal Institute of British Architects After Hunt s death DanielChesterFrench was commissioned to create a memorial consisting of a pair of standing figures representing the arts of Painting Sculpture on one side and of Architecture holding a model of Hunt s Administration building in Chicago on the other both flanking French s portrait of Hunt The memorial is located on Fifth Avenue and th Street in NewYork across the street from the Frick Museum Here is French s maquette for the figure of Architecture inches high bronze ADAAGalleries AmericanSculpture

text: Moving away from the renaissance we back into the middle ages Specifically some arms and armor from different places around the world Europe Japan a dash of the middle East We ll get to that later I could gush about the Islamic empire for five hours I m not a fan of war or death However military history strategy and technology are fascinating to me It s like watching a tactical game more fascinating than many fantasy stories and scientific advancements that were only thought of due to the pressures and hardships of war Despite many of the Rough elements of the time period There s a lot that fascinates me about it and that I enjoy hearing about studying middleages medival armor armsandarmor weapons medivalwar knight knights samurai metropolitanmuseumofart metropolitain met museum strategy

text: The Horse Fair by Rosa Bonheur s The Horse Fair depicts dealers selling horses at the horse market held on the Boulevard de l H pital Paris The notorious hospital of Salp tri re can be seen in the left background Bonheur submitted it to the Salon of This work led to Bonheur s international fame and recognition Rosalia Shriver writes When it was finally finished and exhibited at the Salon of its creator was only years old Yet no other woman had ever achieved a work of such force and brilliance and no other animal painter had produced a work of such size Bonheur painted The Horse Fair from a series of sketches of Percherons and other draft horses which she had made at the Paris horse market on the Boulevard de l H pital She attended the market twice weekly for a year and a half from summer of to the end of She sought a permission de travestissement from the Paris police to dress as a man to avoid drawing attention to herself In she had studied at a Paris slaughterhouse a typical activity for an animal painter and experienced harassment as a visible woman In addition to studies at the Paris horse market she also modeled her animals on those from the Paris Omnibus Company It has been suggested that one of the human figures is a self portrait The first engraving of the work was made by Jules Jacques Veyrassat during the Paris Salon of while the often reproduced engraving by Thomas Landseer helped it achieve a wide popularity Painter Molly Luce claimed that The Horse Fair was the first work which influenced her in her decision to become an artist and the work also inspired a young Wayne Thiebaud Boneur s brother Isidore Bonheur cast a bronze relief plaque based on the painting for her monument at Fontainebleau In the literary world The Horse Fair inspired a anthology by poet Robin Becker The painting was bought by art dealer Ernest Gambart then William Parkinson Wright then A T Stewart and then Cornelius Vanderbilt II who later donated it to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York in art wikipedia org

text: Hey guys Long time no talk posts anything at all Here are a couple of my Friday thoughts This is a painting that stopped me at metmuseum this summer I am a girl just like her I stare out of windows Sometimes because I m longing Sometimes because I m lost Sometimes because the sunlight just drenches me with joy Sometimes because rain makes me giddy Sometimes because watching people is really funny Sometimes because it s not Sometimes because I m actually just staring out the window steadying my gaze while I wander around a memory in my mind s eye Everythinggggggg feels so poignant and temporal and nostalgic right now And its brilliant and it hurts at the same time I just binge watched the first season of Fleabag last night and ate two huge pieces of cake Glean from that what you will I am anchored by this right now Joy is not made to be a crumb Which is from a Mary Oliver poem aRe We ShOcKeD If you know me you know that I read her poetry almost every day I am so thankful for my life and every little ordinary thing in it that I could just cry I decided I would keep this account for little moments like this and see if makes anyone feel a little less lonely and a little more inspired Because the truth is I just don t love social media enough to keep it up consistently But she will be here for these little windows that you are more than welcome to sit and look out of It s a harvest moon tonight don t miss it Much love y all balthus ordinarythings metropolitanmuseumofart metmuseum maryoliverpoetry autumnalthoughts harvestmoon manisagiddything

text: b o o k r e v i e w When I heard that The Goldfinch was being made into a movie I immediately set a goal that I had to read it before the movie came out today sept I had previously read Donna Tartt s The Secret History and loved it so I figured I would enjoy The Goldfinch as well In case you don t know The Goldfinch centers around a NYC boy Theo in the aftermath of a life changing explosion at the Met Tragically Theo lost his mother in the explosion but he walked out with a world famous painting The Goldfinch that would take him on a journey that would last a decade Overall I enjoyed this book and once you finish reading my thoughts on it you ll probably be confused as to why I rated it so high but like I said I did like it as a whole First off I find this book to be kind of like watching the bachelor or pretty little liars I don t really like it or any of the people but I can t stop watching cause I want to know what happens For a large chunk of this book I literally had no idea what the plot was It read kind of like Napoleon Dynamite where it s soooo long but literally nothing happens The rising action is so drawn out only for the climax falling action and resolution to take place within the last pages of this page novel How annoying Also because I have a short attention span with books like this that I kind of find boring I ll skim until I get to a part that interests me so I completely missed the racist comments that come out of Boris mouth and when I heard about them I obviously saw the book in kind of a new light I do totally agree that Tartt s work lacks diversity but I also think she s obsessed with WASPs cause the same type of characters filled The Secret History so it didn t necessarily shock me Will I ever read this again No Will I see the movie Probably even though critics also said that basically nothing happens in this movie until the end Now for the big shock lol Alison s rating honestly if this book was anything under a for me I would ve just stopped reading it s too long to commit to if I didn t like it Please share your thoughts on the book with me in the comments

text: SITAR HUNT This is a moment of pride for EVERY Indian artist musician So a while ago I got to know through a friend that there is a Sitar made by my Grand father at the MET museum and I had been longing to go since a looong time and I finally went there Turns out it was made by my dad for my Guru Pandit Ravi Shankar in I cannot explain how much pride I take in this instrument as it signifies not only my culture and music but also a homage to my Guru my great grandpa my grandpa and my father sanjayrikhiram Sanjay Rikhiram It s LITERALLY my Guru and my Family in an instrument five miles from where I live For those of you living in the tristate area haven t been to this exhibition please pay a visit and tell them Rishab sent you The sitar is only there for a couple more weeks Here a selection of pictures of me being me captured by closeknit design sitar indianclassical metropolitanmuseumofart artistsoninstagram newyorkcity newyork indianclassicalmusic rikhiram thebeatles sanjayrikhiram ravishankar georgeharrison woodstock montereypopfestival luthier themet art musicartist artist musicalinstrument indian rocknroll halloffame proudindian indianculture metmuseum rockhall rikhiramofficialstore britishmuseum

text: For Favorite Book Friday I m sharing The Goldfinch by Donna Tartt because the movie just came out and I can t wait to see it When a terrorist attack strikes the Met Theo s mother is killed Theo takes a small painting that a dying man seems to be pointing to As Theo adjusts to life with a wealthy school friend and then to living with his alcoholic father in Las Vegas the painting remains with him When Theo returns to New York he eventually enters the underground art dealing world selling fake reproductions of the painting and fears what will happen if he is found out This book was very polarizing some loved it and some hated it but I strongly feel that it s worth it especially because of the unexpected plot twist towards the end

text: Treasure Emperor Caracalla AD Civilization Ancient Rome Where NewYork Metropolitan MuseumPhoto metmuseum Family europe treasures contemporary treasures tesori italiani Caracalla took the official name of M Aurelius Antoninus Pius as part of the Severan dynasty s attempt to appear as the legitimate and worthy successors of the secondcentury Antonine emperors Despite this in his official portraiture he abandoned the luxuriant hair and beard of his predecessors for a military style characterized by closely cropped curls and a stubble beard An ancient source records that on his deathbed his father Septimius Severus advised Caracalla to enrich the soldiers and despise everyone else This finely carved head is a powerful rendering of the official portrait and was probably produced at an imperial workshop since the statue fragments are said to have been found in Rome italy italia archaeology archeologia arqueologia arqueolog a roman roma imperio romanhistory history metropolitanmuseumofart historia archeologie emperor romanart metmuseum ancientrome imperoromano metmuseum

text: In newyork one can consume art like a Starbucks coffee It is just everywhere some of them is cheap to the level that you wonder why is there even a need to buy one In timesquare one can buy a framed picture for while you can t buy anything with the same price in a nearby McDonalds But some of them are exceptional so much so that are hailed at one of the most exquisite museums in the world such as metropolitanmuseumofart guggenheimmuseum rubinmuseum I mean I can t keep up with the list of museums that ny offer Why is that We consider ourselves smart educated and progressive yet sometimes we fail to appreciate the high art and buy the worthless one But who s counting really In this day and age we only buy art we can afford to appreciate and that freedom is ours newyorkcity newyorkart artscene posesforpictures sohonyc beartsy whatisart travelholic travelmania thoughtoftheday inspiration loveyourself thebigapple cityoflove becreative crazytimes

text: Reminiscing tonight about my life and friends in NYC This is a drawing of a sculpture in the MetropolitanMuseumofArt I took a classical figure drawing class at HunterCollege with Anthony Panzera some years ago which changed and expanded my art life in ways I never imagined Every week I spent time in the MetMuseum drawing a classical sculpture and discovered that new techniques I was learning not only improved my drawings but also opened my attentiveness to the world around me in surprising ways I m very thankful for that and for these drawings which are artifacts of that learning pencil graphite graphitedrawing classicalfigure classicalfiguredrawing renaissancedrawing figuredrawing pencilart

text: Water of the Flowery Mill is part of a group of landscape inspired works that Gorky produced during the last six years of his life Based on his study of an old mill and bridge on the Housatonic River in Connecticut it also evokes the artist s nostalgia for Armenia from which he and his family had fled some twenty years earlier Influenced by Surrealism Gorky s fluid biomorphic abstraction translates the landscape into flat overlapping fields of colour and seems to anticipate the gestural brushwork of Abstract Expressionism a movement that emerged in the s MET Water of the Flowery Mill by Armenian born American artist Arshile Gorky metmuseum arshilegorky americanartists biomorphicabstraction armenianroots landscapepaintings myphoto myphotography personalreflections metropolitanmuseumofart newyorkgalleries artoftheday arthistory artoflooking artobserved artblogging loveart arttalks artbites brilliantcolours whatdoyousee

text: Esta exhibici n del MET en Nueva York me encant tanto que fui dos veces Tuve la suerte de verla antes que se terminara Comparto mis recuerdos con Uds Pueden ver m s en el story Camp Notes on Fashion es la exposici n de arte de alta moda del del Centro de Disfraces Anna Wintour en el Met de Nueva York Su curador es Andrew Bolton A trav s de m s de objetos que datan desde el siglo XVII hasta el presente la exposici n de primavera del del Instituto del Traje explora los or genes de la est tica exuberante del campamento El ensayo de de Susan Sontag Notes on Camp proporciona el marco para la exposici n que examina c mo los elementos de iron a humor parodia pastiche artificio teatralidad y exageraci n se expresan en la moda I was so lucky to be able to visit the Camp Notes on Fashion exhibition at the Met I love it so much that I went twice It s a shame its already over Camp Notes on Fashion is the high fashion art exhibition of the Anna Wintour Costume Center at the Met in New York Its curator is Andrew Bolton Through more than objects dating from the seventeenth century to the present The Costume Institute s spring exhibition explores the origins of camp s exuberant aesthetic Susan Sontag s essay Notes on Camp provides the framework for the exhibition which examines how the elements of irony humor parody pastiche artifice theatricality and exaggeration are expressed in fashion You can see more of the exhibit on the story style ootd love instagood instafashion fashionblogger fashionista campnotesonfashion metcamp notesoncamp susansontag fashionexhibition exhibitiondesign fashion themet metropolitanmuseumofart campy Costumeinstitute

text: Untitled Studio by Kerry James Marshall From the Met Marshall often recounts an episode from his summer course at the Otis Art Institute after seventh grade when he visited the studio of his childhood idol Charles White It was the first time Marshall had seen an artist s workspace in person and also the moment he realized that making pictures was something he too could do In part about that discovery of a black artist s workshop a place of labor where an allegorical catalogue of all modes of art making is on display Untitled Studio is a majestic ode to the job of the artist the history of the medium and the multiple possibilities that still pump through the heart of painting kerryjamesmarshall metropolitanmuseumofart contemporaryart contemporarypainting acryliconpvc acryliconpvcpanel davidzwirner davidzwirnergallery shareblackstories africanamericanart africanamericanartist

text: PEER SMED As a gold carver a silversmith As a designer of iron grilles Peer Smed was born inCopenhagen he became an expert metalcraft and produced objects somewhat in the Jensen style but with characteristic touches that clearly marked them as his His obituary spoke of his honors as a gold carver a silversmith and as a designer of iron grilles He was also proficient in copper and bronze he exhibited his work at the Brooklyn Museum of Art the Metropolitan Museum of Art and galleries in New York and San Francisco Smed produced the elaborate doors designed by William Zorach for the entrance to the Schwarzenbach Building in New York City and created silver designs for Tiffany and Company His work is currently held in the Brooklyn Museum of Art the Metropolitan Museum of Art the Dallas Museum of Art and the Art Institute of Chicago as well as several private galleries and collections around the country Gallery is offering a collection of Peer Smed silver collection athttps www gallery com search q peer smed persmed georgjensen silversmith silver brooklynmuseumofart metropolitanmuseumofart copenhagendesign tiffany contemporaryjewelry

name: 2019-09-18 04.20.09 2135135515381255873_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: GLENN LIGON America rubellcollection This semester I m taking a class about the groundbreaking exhibition Americans which presents work by many of the world s most influential black artists I am so excited about this class because we will help curate the show when it moves to the Barnes Foundation in late October I have to write about a few artworks each week so I ve decided to pare down my responses and share them with you guys too Glenn Ligon is known for using language to explore themes of race sexuality and identity Ligon employs text from important authors like James Baldwin and Zora Neale Hurston repeating famous lines in neon and writing out entire passages in charcoal So it is interesting that his most recognizable and perhaps most compelling work consists of a single word America What makes this artwork special is its immediacy and accessibly two things that are not always the case with Ligon The most effective aspect of this artwork though is its ambiguity Anyone can approach the work and draw their own unique conclusions about its meaning Some may see the work and feel a sense of national pride while others may read it as a symbol of oppression Hence Ligon is exposing the dichotomies embedded in our American system with a particular focus on race and class The work makes me question how and why my reaction might differ from that of a black woman or an undocumented immigrant How does my experience my privilege as a white male define my understanding of America As I think about this work I can t help but liken it to Jasper Johns s Flag paintings form the mid s Johns similarly explored America s social differences in the midst of the Civil Rights Movement and the Cold War Perhaps fittingly Ligon s work revisited these important questions as we entered a new period of social and economic turmoil in If some of this looks familiar thats because I recycled some thoughts from the very similar Jasper Johns painting I posted last week

text: Do something new day A Visit to the Metropolitan Museum to see old favorites and discover new ones Anne and I focused intently on getting to the Lehman Wing to see Botticelli s extraordinary Annunciation which we studied in art History class at Sweet Briar College The carefully composed painting with strong architectural elements focuses us on the divine interaction between Mary and Gabriel we discussed it and reveled in its beauty A mindful looking meditation The El Greco room was newly installed and looked glorious Paused to examine Leonardo da Vinci s St Jerome a single unfinished painting from the Vatican in a room to itself Uplifting and thoughtful interpretation provided new insights to the craft of painting metropolitanmuseumofart friendsforever friendship elgreco botticelli africanart hawaiianfeatherwork leonardodavincipainting explore discover learning observing awe chronicpain chronicillness spoonie dosomething dosomethingnew bonniepitmandosomethingnew newexperience newart newideas somethingnew happymoments happyday artmuseum

text: Have you seen the bust of the Voldemort look alike at the Met Discover connections like this in an interactive wizarding tour in the magical Metropolitan Museum with fableandlark inspired by harrypotter We had so much fun with our Potterhead neighbor she s read the whole series times and now we re so exited to get through the rest of the books currently in the middle of See spaces places and objects similar to those in the books from part of an actual castle to depictions of mythical creatures like griffins and dragons Includes scavenger hunts creative activities fun items to take home and some spell casting Halloween tours coming soon Costumes are always encouraged but my daughter just wanted Hermione hair that day metmuseum themet metamericanwing americanwing

text: More from the Met Louis Comfort Tiffany s Garden Landscape is one of my favorite Met moments Tiffany s work in mosaic inspired by Byzantine examples he had seen abroad dates to as early as the s when he began experimenting with iridescent glass and transparent tesserae backed with metal leaf Mosaic decoration graced countless interiors by him from churches to department stores The culmination of his interest was the vast Dream Garden mosaic created in after designs by Maxfield Parrish for Edward Bok at the Curtis Publishing Company in Philadelphia Tiffany may have made this shimmering garden landscape as a preliminary study for the Curtis commission It was among the decorations that graced the Tiffany showrooms until their contents were auctioned in metropolitanmuseumofart louiscomforttiffany theamericanwing mosaic
