text: Beautiful lunch with my colleagues livingcafesg My first at a raw and plant based cuisine restaurant although they do serve limited options of fish and poultry And the food is really delicious Seen in picture raw roasted broccoli and mushroom pizza Pad Thai noodles are made from raw zucchini raw Mexican chips with dips and my selection of main course Wild Barramundi served with Mexican and and pesto sauce The raw pizza is my favourite super tasty and flavourful Birthday cake is a slice of raw carrot cake yummy It s an early birthday celebration and I m wearing my new birthday gift from Met Museum a replica from a piece worn by the Venus Goddess of Love in a painting by Peter Paul Rubens Thank you to my leadership team for this special and memorable treat rawcuisine birthdaycelebrations metropolitanmuseumofart artnfashion peterpaulrubens whatatreat thankyou

text: A few more guitars from the Play It Loud Instruments of Rock and Roll exhibit at metropolitanmuseum Telecasters from Keith Richards and Bruce Springsteen seeing those two were stunning plus guitars from Muddy Waters the mother instrument of rock n roll Bo Diddley The Everly Brothers John Lennon Jimi Hendrix the guitar he played at Woodstock Pete Townsend and Eddie Van Halen s famous handmade Frankenstein guitar So close that I could almost touch them Or at least get arrested for trying I m such a nerd The exhibit runs through October You still have a chance to check it out for yourself Trust me you won t be disappointed adventuresindogsandrealestate petfriendlyrealtor petfriendly realestateagent realtorlife nycphotographer nycphotography playitloud guitars metropolitanmuseumofart newyork nyc themet thebeatles johnlennon keithrichards rollingstones cityphotography brucespringsteen igphoto jimihendrix thewho photography vanhalen ig nyc photographer midtownmanhattan midtown museum

text: I m a sucker for performance art My body like yours is a museum that holds a collection of memories As an artist I try to hold a mirror up to the world and capture what is being reflected I am not a historian My eyes ears nose mouth stomach legs and hands are the filters through which I experience the history embedded in the objects and spaces in the physical world and the narratives around them Memory is ultimately of the body for me and for you Nikhil Chopra Artist in Residence for the metmuseum

text: Today I explored Manhattan on foot I started from home in the UpperWestSide walked through CentralPark with Taylor and dropped him off at the hospital Then I headed downtown from the UpperEastSide and made my way through some amazing streets and spots like MadisonAvenue thavenue parkavenue and saw the guggenheim metropolitanmuseumofart themet and window shopped at places I couldn t afford like gucci versace fendi prada louisvuitton and givenchy Then I made my way through timessquare and saw the empirestatebuilding the flatironbuilding and so much more I walked through soho and nolita which may be my favorite place in the city because it reminded me so much of the bywater in NewOrleans I made it past chinatown and up to a killer rooftop view in the boweryhotel I kept going to the brooklynbridge through the financial district down wallstreet and all the way to batterypark for an amazing sunset And on the th mile I rested

text: I ll spare you the lame Gossip Girl References but sitting on the Met Steps is an NYC tradition that has withstood the test of time The Metropolitan Museum of Art of New York City known colloquially as the Met is the largest art museum in the United States The Metropolitan Museum of Art was founded in for the purposes of opening a museum to bring art and art education to the American people The museum was reported as having million visitors during the past year Did you know the Met is home to the world s oldest surviving piano The antique instrument dates back to and was created by Bartolomeo Cristofori the Italian man who is credited with inventing the piano Interestingly enough the official mascot for the Metropolitan museum is an ancient Egyptian hippopotamus Wether you re snacking on the steps or exploring inside the museum it s well worth a visit themet metsteps gossipgirl xoxogossipgirl MetropolitanMuseumofArt manhattan streetsofnewyork nyc streetphotography newyork newyorkcity explorenyc nyctravel usa nomadiclife paddington paddingtonbear abearcalledpaddington worldtraveler travelplushie travelplush plushiesofinstagram travelbear kawaii plush plushie plushies plushtoy plushielife plushiefriends

text: Frederick Wellington Ruckstull American born France Breitenbach New York Ruckstull intended Evening to portray an ideal rather than a specific being It illustrates his observation that e verything in nature folds at evening The voluptuous figure in a contrapposto stance tucks her face under her raised bent right arm and her drowsy distant expression suggests the approach of sleep newyork art metropolitanmuseumofart museum history traveling trip vacation

text: One year ago today was one of the best days of my life I walked into TheMetropolitan Museum of Art in New York and saw my products in the gift shop representing the exhibit dedicated to my motherland Armenia The long journey leading up to that opening day taught me the greatest lesson of my life When you want something bad enough there is a specific purpose why THAT yearning has been placed in YOUR heart It s your duty and responsibility to yourself and everyone else in your world to seek it out work towards it to not give up when things get difficult and when you accomplish it share it We were each put on this earth for uniquely designed reasons and every single one of our contributions matter whether they are local or global To fear is human do it anyway followyourdreams itsnevertoolate artistatthemet arpikrikorian themet metarmenia womenartists armenianartist metropolitanmuseumofart armenia yerevan proudarmenian doitanyway

name: 2019-09-22 02.28.16 2137978304473141732_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Took a trip down to the Met yesterday and saw some pieces of wood wire and metal that inspired me so much To see this guitar in person for me was absolutely amazing Eric Clapton s The Fool SG is the guitar that inspired me to play guitar It s literally the machine that started it all for me I remember watching the Cream Farewell Concert as a teen on VHS lol with my buddy and his Dad back in the s before I even played guitar I remember seeing that guitar and thinking it was just the coolest thing I d ever seen I loved the way Clapton played it and just everything about his swagger and that guitar in the interviews on that tape The guitar just looked and sounded so cool A few days later I heard Santana s Samba Pa Ti at a late afternoon almost summer party when I was stoned out of my mind lol That song changed me forever The Fool SG the Cream and that Santana song are the sole reasons I started playing guitar They started it all TheFool EricClapton Cream Gibson SG BluesRock TheMet PlayItLoud Inspiring MyReason psychedelic GuitarPhotography ToneChaser ToneKillers ToneHeaven GuitarSpotter GuitarsDaily MonumentalGuitars GibsonSGLovers GearTalk GearNerds Geartopia Gearphoria GuitarNerd MetropolitanMuseumOfArt NYC Gibsunday on a Straturday gibsonsofinstagram gibsongtrjunkie gibsonguitar gibsongtrjunkie gibsonsofinstagram gibsondaily gibsonoftheday gibsonsg lovers monumentalguitars metmuseum gibsoncustom ericclapton cream blues

text: Oh the beautiful things you see when you look up There are four statues by Kenyan Artist WangechiMutu on the fa ade of the MetropolitanMuseumofArt The installation opened on September th and will run until January Unfortunately absolutely no one at the information desk in the lobby of the museum was aware it was outside It s a shame because the sculptures are so striking The bronze figures of Black women against the Beaux Arts arts facade of The Met are a beautiful contrast It s interesting to see this th century western style building with modern day African sculptures positioned among the colossal columns A placement that I suspect helps with the issue of visitor diversity and Blackartists on view Wangechi Mutu The Seated I II III IV Bronze Artist Statement excerpt The Poised stately figures I have created for The Met fa ade derive inspiration from my interest in ancient and modern practices that reflect on the relationship between women and power across various traditions including the weighty symbols and adornments worn within certain African traditions as well as the cumbersome burdens of ornately clad caryatids I look at the contradictory aspects of such human expressions in which women are respected for their strength resilience and wisdom and yet suffer for it too Wangechi Mutu womeninthearts sculpture blackartist africanart kenyanart artnyc publicarts artinstallation themet contemporaryart soloexhibition sole blackexhibition art

text: The Rocky Mountains Lander s Peak by Albert Bierstadt in The Metropolitan Museum of Art New York This painting is the major work that resulted from the artist s first trip to the West His intention to create panoramic views of the American frontier was apparent by December just before he embarked on the trip In early he accompanied a government survey expedition headed by Frederick W Lander to the Nebraska Territory By summer the party had reached the Wind River Range of the Rocky Mountains in what is now Wyoming Bierstadt dubbed the central mountain in the picture Lander s Peak following the colonel s death in the Civil War This was one of a number of large works painted after Bierstadt s return from these travels It was completed in exhibited to great acclaim and purchased in for the then astounding sum of by James McHenry an American living in London Bierstadt later bought it back and gave or sold it to his brother Edward tbt therockymountainslanderspeak albertbierstadt metropolitanmuseumofart art painting greatpaintings masterpiece nofilter newyork newyorkcity travel vacation wanderlust travelgram instatravel beautifuldestinations aroundtheworld solotravel

text: urban dwelling From Williamsburg Bridge EdwardHopper Here Hopper depicts the austere fa ades of four apartment buildings and reduced the steel suspension bridge that gives the painting its name to the margins Completed in and connecting Brooklyn with Manhattan the structure is indicated only by the unobtrusive railing rising at the slight diagonal along the bottom of the canvas As opposed to focusing on the bridge that facilitates movement in and out of the city Hopper creates an image absent of noise or motion He emphasizes the alienation and anonymity of urbanlife by including a single figure a woman sitting alone in a top story window metmuseum museum artmuseum art modernArt americanpainter arthistory americanmodernism oiloncanvas williamsburg williamsburgbridge newyorkcity newyork nyc latergram themet metropolitanmuseumofart

text: Paul C zanne Seated Peasant oil on canvas cm Metropolitan Museum New York Paul C zanne s art grew out of Impressionism and challenged the conventional values of painting in the th century He insisted on personal expression and the integrity of the painting itself regardless of subject matter C zanne tried to reveal the inner geometry of nature in his work or as he expressed to make of Impressionism something solid and durable C zanne s intellectual approach to formal issues particularly his spatial explorations laid the foundation for Picasso and other artists subsequent explorations with Cubism while his investigations of color and brushstroke influenced Matisse and other Fauve artists in the first decade of the century Although misunderstood and discredited during most of his life over the years the public and critics embraced his work Picasso offered perhaps the most truthful description of C zanne s role for subsequent generations of artists declaring that he was the father of us all Seated Peasant is one of several paintings by C zanne of peasants who worked on the C zanne family estate known as Le Jas de Bouffan The tone and color is similar to his famous series of paintings showing men playing cards The unknown peasant probably sits in the kitchen of Jas de Bouffan His hat is pushed back on his head and his suit has been painted in grey and brown tones Cezanne gives him a calm solid pose devoid of any gesture or expression which lends him a certain solemnity Check out my other accounts art questions and debates my favorite work of art paulcezanne paulc zanne cezanne c zanne thecardplayers cardplayers metropolitanmuseum montsaintevictoire postimpressionism impressionism provence frenchart frenchartist seatedpeasant metropolitanmuseumofart

name: 2019-09-24 10.52.28 2139681626216921038_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Couldn t be more excited to share with you all the centerpiece of metmuseum th anniversary and my life Making The Met opening exactly six months from today One thing that never gets old about working here is the privilege of lifting ropes to go behind the scenes of this storied institution These views date back to our original building on th Avenue designed in the Victorian Gothic style by Calvert Vaux and Jacob Wrey Mould and the names are those who shaped our so called first half century of struggle and growth We ll take a look at the art architecture and people who transformed the Museum during these early formative years up through the present day Come visit between March and August metmondays metmuseum makingthemet met themet metropolitanmuseumofart methistory victoriangothic founders

name: 2019-09-24 10.57.27 2139684137540561043_metropolitanmuseumofart.jpg
text: Today I visited the Antonio Ratti Textile Center at the Met I had an appointment to view some th century coverlets for an upcoming project in my History of Textiles class This was my first time viewing textiles in a museum collection and it was very cool to have a one on one experience with these objects I can t share the photographs I took including one at x magnification but here are some pics from the Met s website One of the coverlets I saw was this double weave coverlet woven by Henry Tyler who lived and worked in Jefferson County NY I love those little lions in the corner blocks weaving textiles textilehistory handweaving themet metropolitanmuseumofart nyc gradschool fashionhistory coverlet doubleweave antoniorattitextilecenter

text: NYC MetMuseum Tonight The Met welcomed members after hours I was asked to be part of the Met Educator team and was assigned the gallery hung with early work by Picasso seen here as well as Matisse and other th c artists whose careers began in the th c I decided to concentrate on the rapid development of Picasso s career in important works I loved researching these works and working on my presentations which were well received And as always it was a great learning experience for me I have an even greater admiration forPicasso s great talent and his artistic daring and creativity picasso pablopicasso metropolitanmuseumofart modernart
